<seg id="1">Report on the results of parallel checks on the management of value added tax between the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic carried out in 2005</seg>
<seg id="2">Introduction Word</seg>
<seg id="3">The material presented reports on the progress and results of parallel checks carried out by the Supreme Audit Office, the Czech Republic and the Najvyšší kontrolní úradom Slovenskej republiky, which focused on the field of value added tax administration and the use of the VIES (Value Added Tax Information Exchange System).</seg>
<seg id="4">In May 2004, the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic joined the European Union, so that the revenue from value added tax affects not only the national budgets of both countries, but also the budget of the European Union as a whole.</seg>
<seg id="5">Parallel control actions were aimed, in particular, at checking the tax authorities' process for examining the amount of value added tax paid in commercial transactions between individual Member States of the European Union.</seg>
<seg id="6">The introduction of VIES made it possible to exchange information electronically on the registration of value added tax payers in the various Member States of the European Union and on commercial transactions carried out by those payers.</seg>
<seg id="7">The discrepancy between the VIES data and the data in the taxpayer's VAT return should alert the tax authorities to suspicious cases and allow tax evasion or fraud to be detected.</seg>
<seg id="8">The benefits of the parallel checks carried out were not only in the exchange of information on the procedure followed by the financial and tax authorities in the administration of value added tax, but in particular in the examination of the use of the VIES system in checking the application of the right to value added tax exemption in intra-Community transactions.</seg>
<seg id="9">The knowledge gained from the implementation of parallel controls is beneficial for the development of mutual cooperation and will be used to carry out further parallel controls in cooperation with the control institutions of the Member States of the European Union.</seg>
<seg id="10">Report on the results of parallel controls on the administration of value added tax for the period 1.5.2004 to 30.6.2005</seg>
<seg id="11">Introduction</seg>
<seg id="12">Control number: (CZ) 05/19 (SK) 22/2005</seg>
<seg id="13">Subject: (CZ) Value Added Tax Administration, (SK) Control of the tax authorities' procedures for the administration, control and enforcement of value added tax and the performance of VIES tasks for the exchange of information between EU Member States</seg>
<seg id="14">The Supreme Audit Office, the Czech Republic (hereinafter referred to as the SAO, the Czech Republic) and the Najvyšší kontrolný úrad Slovenskej republiky (hereinafter referred to as the SAO of the Slovak Republic) concluded a contract on cooperation in auditing activities on 12 September 2005.</seg>
<seg id="15">The subject of the contract was cooperation in the implementation of parallel auditing actions “Value Added Tax Administration”, included in the SAO, Czech Republic's 2005 audit work plan under No 05/19, and “Control of the procedure of tax authorities in the administration, control and recovery of taxes on prized value and fulfilment of roles under the VIES system on the deletion of informácii medzi by the members of ECA”, included in the SAO's audit work plan under No 22/2005.</seg>
<seg id="16">The control actions carried out in parallel were in the nature of coordinated control.</seg>
<seg id="17">The result of the joint coordinated inspection has been processed within the meaning of the European Enforcement Regulation No 31 on INTOSAI control standards.</seg>
<seg id="18">The cooperation consisted of exchanging information to the extent provided for in the contract and producing a joint final report on the outcome of the parallel checks.</seg>
<seg id="19">The purpose of the coordinated inspection was to verify selected cases of supply and acquisition of goods in suspicious commercial transactions between taxpayers of value added tax from the Czech Republic (hereinafter referred to as the Czech Republic) and the Slovak Republic (hereinafter referred to as the ‘SR’).</seg>
<seg id="20">Both parties contractually undertook to provide each other with information from public sources, from the VIES electronic system (Value Added Tax Information Exchange System) and data on requests received and sent to examine commercial transactions between the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="21">The checks were carried out in parallel between June and December 2005.</seg>
<seg id="22">On the territory of the Czech Republic, the control was carried out by the state budget department and territorial departments of central Bohemia, northwestern Bohemia, southern Bohemia, southern Moravia, central Moravia and northern Moravia.</seg>
<seg id="23">The audited persons were the Ministry of Finance and 12 Financial Offices: the Tax Office in Mlada Boleslav, the Tax Office in Kolín, the Tax Office in Teplice, the Financial Office in Karlovy Vary, the Financial Office in Tábor, the Financial Office in Brno III, the Tax Office in Znojma, the Financial Office in Zlín, the Financial Office in Šumperk, the Financial Office in Ostrava I, the Financial Office for Prague 7 and the Financial Office for Prague 9.</seg>
<seg id="24">The audit was carried out in the territory of SR by the Finance and Tax Division of the SAO of the Slovak Republic in cooperation with the SAO Expozituras of Banská Bystrica and Košice on 9 selected tax offices: Bratislava I, Komárno Tax Office, Trenčín Tax Office, Prievidza Daňový úrad, Zvolen Daňový úrad, Dolný Kubín Daňový úrad, Košice II Daňový úrad, Košice V and Michalovce Daňový úrad.</seg>
<seg id="25">Objective of inspections:</seg>
<seg id="26">The aim of the parallel control actions was to examine the procedure of the financial and/or tax authorities in the administration of value added tax (VAT) following the incorporation of the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic into the single internal market of the European Union (EU) and to examine the use of the VIES electronic information system, in particular when checking the application of the right to VAT exemption.</seg>
<seg id="27">The audited period of the coordinated inspection was the period from 1.5.2004 to 30.6.2005.</seg>
<seg id="28">Summary of results and evaluation of parallel control actions An electronic VIES system is in place in EU Member States, allowing tax authorities to check whether a supplier has been authorised to exempt a taxable transaction from VAT and, in the country of destination, to check whether the purchaser has properly declared and taxed the goods acquired.</seg>
<seg id="29">VIES is not centralised within the EU, each Member State develops its own system.</seg>
<seg id="30">The audit found differences in the national VIES systems in the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic in the following areas:</seg>
<seg id="31">The recapitulative statements indicate the values of supplies of goods to other EU Member States, the values of services provided are not included in recapitulative statements.</seg>
<seg id="32">Data from summary reports filed by Czech payers are processed at the level of tax authorities in the Czech Republic, where they are compared with data on supplies of goods to other EU Member States included in VAT returns.</seg>
<seg id="33">The tax authorities transmit the data from the recapitulative statements to the Ministry of Finance (CLO), which sends them to the other EU Member States.</seg>
<seg id="34">In SR, data from recapitulative statements filed by Slovak taxpayers at tax offices are only converted into electronic form and processed centrally at the Tax Directorate of SR (CLO).</seg>
<seg id="35">In the Czech Republic, payers report the value of supplies of goods and services to other EU Member States on separate lines of VAT returns, which makes it possible to compare the values reported in the recapitulative statements with the values of supplies of goods according to VAT tax returns and to identify any differences between them.</seg>
<seg id="36">In SR, the values of goods and services supplied to other EU Member States are reported cumulatively on a common line of VAT return.</seg>
<seg id="37">As a result, in SR, the system does not make it possible to automatically identify differences between the values of supplies of goods according to VAT returns and recapitulative statements.</seg>
<seg id="38">Separate reporting of goods delivery values in VAT returns allows the results of data reconciliation to be used in controlling VAT exemption of supplies of goods to the EU.</seg>
<seg id="39">The data received from the recapitulative statements filed by payers in other EU Member States are processed into CLOs and compared with the value of acquisitions of goods declared by payers from the Czech Republic and SR respectively in VAT returns.</seg>
<seg id="40">In the SR, these data are sent to the tax authorities, and the tax authorities decide for themselves which cases of difference to examine.</seg>
<seg id="41">In the Czech Republic, the Ministry of Finance (CLO) determines which quantified differences between the values of delivery and acquisition of goods must be checked by the tax authorities, and gives a list of these cases to the tax authorities responsible locally.</seg>
<seg id="42">This ensures that, for the most significant derogations, it will be verified that VAT was correctly declared when the goods were acquired.</seg>
<seg id="43">Furthermore, the audit highlighted some problems in the VAT management system due to the different reporting of intra-Community transactions (i.e. supplies and acquisitions of goods made by payers from different EU Member States):</seg>
<seg id="44">Summary reports are filed in the EU for each calendar quarter and the maximum period for processing and sending data to other EU Member States is set at 3 months from the end of the respective quarter.</seg>
<seg id="45">Reducing the reporting period of recapitulative statements to one month, together with reducing the processing time, would allow earlier access to VIES data.</seg>
<seg id="46">Tax authorities would thus be able to check more effectively whether VAT was declared at the correct amount when intra-Community acquisitions were made.</seg>
<seg id="47">At the same time, the submission of VAT returns and recapitulative statements for the same tax year (month) would allow quicker verification of whether the payer has declared in both the recapitulative statement and the VAT return the same value of the supplies of goods to the EU.</seg>
<seg id="48">Differences between EU-payer declared goods delivery values and those reported by CR and SR payers were due, among other things, to different reporting of intra-Community supplies and acquisitions data across EU Member States.</seg>
<seg id="49">These were, for example, the presentation in recapitulative statements of advance payments received, or the presentation in a supplier's recapitulative statement of intra-Community supplies in a quarter other than intra-Community acquisitions in the acquirer's VAT return.</seg>
<seg id="50">The harmonisation of the conditions for reporting such data within the EU would lead to streamlining of the control activities of national tax administrations.</seg>
<seg id="51">The cooperation of the SAO, the Czech Republic and the SAO of the Slovak Republic was also aimed at examining selected intra-Community transactions carried out between the two states.</seg>
<seg id="52">A total of 40 cases of commercial transactions between 29 Czech and 32 Slovak tax entities were examined together, where there were doubts about their implementation or suspicions of VAT evasion.</seg>
<seg id="53">The SAO, the Czech Republic and the SAO of the Slovak Republic have found out the following:</seg>
<seg id="54">tax entities have declared in their VAT returns for the purpose of unduly obtaining an excess VAT deduction the execution of intra-Community transactions which have not actually been carried out;</seg>
<seg id="55">Tax Entities reported intra-Community deliveries in carousel transactions, in which there were deliberate multiple decreases in the value of the deliveries in order to draw excessive VAT deductions;</seg>
<seg id="56">suppliers declared in their VAT returns and recapitulative statements intra-Community supplies of goods exempt from VAT to purchasers who were so-called "lost companies" and did not declare the tax on the goods acquired;</seg>
<seg id="57">the suppliers made an intra-Community supply of VAT-exempt goods to tax entities which were not registered for VAT in another Member State.</seg>
<seg id="58">In those cases, the supply should not have been exempt from VAT and should have been subject to tax in the supplier's country;</seg>
<seg id="59">suppliers declared intra-Community supplies in their VAT returns at a higher value than the intra-Community acquisitions declared by the acquirers, in some cases with an incorrect amount of VAT declared.</seg>
<seg id="60">The lessons learned from the audit action showed that VIES provides tax administrations with the information necessary to check the correct application of VAT in intra-Community transactions.</seg>
<seg id="61">In particular, tax administrations should pay close attention to rigorously examining the differences between the data reported by VAT payers and the VIES data and using any information in tax proceedings.</seg>
<seg id="62">Value Added Tax Issues After the Czech Republic and Slovak Republic Join the EU</seg>
<seg id="63">Value Added Tax</seg>
<seg id="64">On 1 May 2004, the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic became members of the EU.</seg>
<seg id="65">Internal borders and border controls on the movement of goods within EU territory have been abolished since EU accession.</seg>
<seg id="66">Until 30.4.2004, the VAT administrator was the competent financial and tax office, with the exception of the importation of goods and occasional bus services within the country, where the tax authority was the customs office.</seg>
<seg id="67">In the context of the adoption of the new Act No 235/2004 Coll. on Value Added Tax (hereinafter referred to as "Act No 235/2004 Coll.") and Act No 222/2004 Col. on Value Added Tax (hereinafter referred to as "Act No 222/2004 Coll."), the administration of VAT on the acquisition of goods and services (formerly imports) from other EU Member States has shifted from customs offices to financial and tax offices respectively.</seg>
<seg id="68">The supply of goods in the Czech Republic, according to the provisions of Section 13 of Act No 235/2004 Coll., means the transfer of the right to dispose of goods as owner.</seg>
<seg id="69">The delivery of goods from the Czech Republic to another EU Member State is the delivery of goods that have actually been dispatched or transported to another EU Member State.</seg>
<seg id="70">Pursuant to Article 64 of Law 235/2004 Coll., a taxable transaction is exempt with the right to deduct VAT if the goods are supplied to a person registered for VAT in another EU Member State.</seg>
<seg id="71">A supply of goods in SR under the provisions of Article 8 of Act No 222/2004 Z. z. is a supply of tangible property in which the right to property is altered.</seg>
<seg id="72">The transfer of goods owned by a taxable person from the territory of the country to another Member State shall also be regarded as a supply of goods if those goods are dispatched or transported by that person or on his behalf to another Member State for the purposes of his business.</seg>
<seg id="73">Pursuant to Article 43 of Act No 222/2004 Z. z., the supply of goods from the national territory to another Member State is exempt from VAT if the purchaser is a person identified for VAT in another Member State.</seg>
<seg id="74">Acquisition of goods from another EU Member State in the Czech Republic pursuant to Section 16 of Act No 235/2004 Coll. is the acquisition of the right to dispose as owner of goods that are dispatched or transported to the customer by a person registered for VAT in another EU Member State.</seg>
<seg id="75">The Czech payer purchases goods at a VAT-free price and is obliged to declare VAT in the Czech Republic according to the provisions of Section 25 of Act No 235/2004 Coll., if he fulfils the conditions of Section 73 of this Act, he is entitled to deduct VAT.</seg>
<seg id="76">Acquisition of goods domestically from another EU Member State in SR, pursuant to Article 11 of Act No 222/2004 Z. z., means the acquisition of the right to dispose as owner of movable tangible property dispatched or transported to the person acquiring it by or on behalf of the supplier or the person acquiring it within the country from another Member State.</seg>
<seg id="77">The SR tax becomes chargeable to the payer when the goods are acquired within the country from another Member State in accordance with the provisions of Article 20 of Act No 222/2004 Z.z.</seg>
<seg id="78">Under Paragraph 49 of Act No 222/2004, the taxpayer may deduct VAT if the tax is charged by him on the acquisition within the country of goods from another Member State in accordance with Paragraphs 11 and 11a of that Act.</seg>
<seg id="79">Three-digit trade is, according to the provisions of Section 17 of Act No 235/2004 Coll. and/or Section 45 of Act No 222/2004 Z. z., a trade concluded between three persons registered for VAT in three different EU Member States where the object of the trade is the supply of the same goods between the three persons.</seg>
<seg id="80">Intra-unitary transactions are supplies and acquisitions of goods made between VAT payers from different EU Member States.</seg>
<seg id="81">The total volumes of intra-Community transactions made between the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic are shown in the table below.</seg>
<seg id="82">VIES system</seg>
<seg id="83">A VAT information exchange system has been set up within the EU to control the exercise of the right to VAT exemption on intra-Community supplies of goods.</seg>
<seg id="84">It includes the VIES electronic system, which allows EU Member State tax authorities to check whether the supplier has been entitled to exempt the taxable transaction from VAT and vice versa, whether the purchaser has properly declared and taxed the goods acquired.</seg>
<seg id="85">The VIES information system is not centralised within the EU.</seg>
<seg id="86">Each Member State develops its own VIES system.</seg>
<seg id="87">The national systems work on a common principle and are interconnected via a common EU communication network, the Common Communication Network (CCN; see diagram below).</seg>
<seg id="88">In the Czech Republic, the VIES system was linked to the Automated Tax Information System (‘ADIS’), in the Slovak Republic with the Tax Information System Application Software (‘APV DIS’).</seg>
<seg id="89">These systems are used by the financial and tax authorities as technical support for executive and management activities in the management of taxes and charges.</seg>
<seg id="90">International administrative cooperation</seg>
<seg id="91">Through international administrative cooperation, the tax administration of each EU country receives information on tax entities that it would not be able to obtain on its own without such cooperation.</seg>
<seg id="92">The main objective of international administrative cooperation is to combat tax evasion and tax losses.</seg>
<seg id="93">Under Council Regulation (EC) No 1798/2003, each Member State establishes a central department within the internal organisational structure in the field of administrative cooperation between EU Member States in the management of VAT, the Central Liaison Office (CLO).</seg>
<seg id="94">In the Czech Republic, the Ministry of Finance – Central Financial and Tax Directorate, where the International Cooperation in VAT Administration Unit (hereinafter referred to as the MF CLO) has been established, performs the tasks arising from international cooperation.</seg>
<seg id="95">The function of the CLO in the SR is fulfilled by the Tax Directorate of the SR, the Department of International Administrative Cooperation (DR CLO).</seg>
<seg id="96">These departments communicate with EU foreign administrations in particular in the area of exchange of information under VIES, exchange of spontaneous information and information at the request of EU tax administrations, coordination of multilateral (simultaneous) tax controls, verification of tax identification numbers (TIN) of persons registered for VAT in other EU Member States and communicate with the European Commission.</seg>
<seg id="97">In order to examine a particular intra-Community transaction or to obtain further information relating to a particular tax entity, the financial and tax authorities send requests for information to the EU via MF CLO or DR CLO respectively.</seg>
<seg id="98">Through these requests, they obtain information from the requested Member States which they can use to correctly determine VAT.</seg>
<seg id="99">Requests for information are sent mostly in electronic form between the CLOs of EU Member States, using the standardised SCAC form.</seg>
<seg id="100">Selected control findings when verifying business transactions</seg>
<seg id="101">The cooperation of the SAO, the Czech Republic and the SAO of the Slovak Republic was mainly aimed at examining selected intra-Community transactions carried out between the two states, as well as the level of use of information obtained through international cooperation by the financial and tax authorities.</seg>
<seg id="102">The SAO, Czech Republic, requested the SAO SR to verify in 30 cases the business transactions carried out between 19 Czech and 25 Slovak tax entities.</seg>
<seg id="103">The SAO requested the SAO of the Czech Republic to verify in 10 cases the business transactions carried out between 7 Slovak and 10 Czech tax entities.</seg>
<seg id="104">Examination of intra-Community transactions revealed, inter alia:</seg>
<seg id="105">o</seg>
<seg id="106">The SAO, Czech Republic asked the SAO SR to verify the procedure of the tax administration, which was sent a reply to the request for information.</seg>
<seg id="107">The Slovak Tax Office requested through the SCAC form a verification of the delivery of goods (footwear) in Q3 2004 from a Slovak payer worth 2 847 thousand Sk.</seg>
<seg id="108">The Tax Office in the Czech Republic replied that the Czech payer had declared the acquisition of the goods at this value only in a supplementary VAT return and had returned the same goods to Slovak tax entities worth CZK 2,550,000 by the end of 2004.</seg>
<seg id="109">Based on the international cooperation of the SAO, the Czech Republic and the SAO SR, it was found that the tax office of the Slovak supplier has fully recognised the right to an excess VAT deduction arising, inter alia, from this supply.</seg>
<seg id="110">This tax office did not provide information about the suspected re-export to the tax authorities locally responsible buyers of goods imported back from the Czech payer.</seg>
<seg id="111">This will provide an impetus for further examination of trading activities in relation to possible carousel fraud.</seg>
<seg id="112">o</seg>
<seg id="113">The Czech tax administrator requested through the SCAC form a verification of the delivery of a technology line to SR worth 4,850,000 CZK in the 2nd quarter of 2004.</seg>
<seg id="114">The tax procedure carried out in SR showed that only part of the technology line was delivered, components worth CZK 3,395,000 were not delivered.</seg>
<seg id="115">In examining this case, the SAO SR found that the VAT on the taxable transaction carried out was declared by the Slovak taxpayer on the amount of CZK 4 850,000 in the VAT return (DAP) for tax year 7/2004.</seg>
<seg id="116">The SAO, Czech Republic also found that the Czech payer had reported in his DAP an excess VAT deduction of CZK 655,000 for that quarter, which was generated by the application of a VAT deduction on the purchase of this technology line from another domestic payer.</seg>
<seg id="117">Based on the results of the investigation, the Czech Tax Office concluded that the Czech and Slovak Tax Entities had formed a business relationship for the purpose of illegally obtaining an excess VAT deduction, disputed the realisation of the taxable transaction and failed to recognise part of the Czech taxpayer's right to deduct the amount of CZK 647,000.</seg>
<seg id="118">o</seg>
<seg id="119">The Slovak tax administration requested in 2004, via the SCAC form, a verification of the supply of goods (copying machines) to the Czech payer worth 24 246K Sk made in December 2002.</seg>
<seg id="120">These goods were purchased by a Slovak payer in November 2002 in SR from another tax entity for a value of 29 667 thousand Sk and subsequently sold to a Czech payer.</seg>
<seg id="121">The Slovak taxpayer claimed an excess VAT deduction for the relevant tax period.</seg>
<seg id="122">A tax investigation carried out in the Czech Republic found that the Czech tax entity did not cooperate with the tax administration and did not file DAPs for the 4th quarter of 2002 or the following period.</seg>
<seg id="123">The SAO SR found that the Slovak tax administration, based on the outcome of the tax inspection, did not recognise the right to an excess deduction of EUR 5 541 000. Sk applied in the DAP for the month of 11/2002 and set the tax liability at 1 750 thousand Sk.</seg>
<seg id="124">At the same time, that taxpayer was not granted a VAT exemption in respect of exports of goods in December 2002.</seg>
<seg id="125">o</seg>
<seg id="126">The Czech tax administrator received an order from MF CLO to verify the value of the purchased goods for Q3 2004.</seg>
<seg id="127">According to the VIES data, the Czech payer was to purchase from SR goods (diluent) worth 3,767 thou.</seg>
<seg id="128">This tax entity did not cooperate with the tax administration, did not file a DAP and was assessed ex officio VAT for months 7 to 12/2004 at the rate of 0 CZK.</seg>
<seg id="129">The Czech tax administrator asked through the SCAC form to verify whether the delivery of goods from SR to the Czech Republic took place, in what quantity and price (according to invoices).</seg>
<seg id="130">In reply, Slovakia's locally competent tax office sent a copy of the invoice, the bill of lading and a demand for payment of the invoice.</seg>
<seg id="131">The SAO SR found that the Slovak payer was granted an exemption with a right to deduct VAT on that supply.</seg>
<seg id="132">The SAO, Czech Republic found that the Czech tax administration had assessed the response to the request for information received from SR as evidence showing that the company had acquired goods from another EU Member State.</seg>
<seg id="133">Upon further investigation, the Tax Office in the Czech Republic will request a superior authority to review the tax liability.</seg>
<seg id="134">o</seg>
<seg id="135">The Slovak company supplied goods (particle products) to, among others, an American company that deposited these goods in the Czech Republic in a free zone.</seg>
<seg id="136">The operator of this free zone was listed on invoices as the consignee of the goods.</seg>
<seg id="137">In 2004, for example, an American company purchased $57,600 worth of particle board from a Slovak payer (at a unit price of $100/piece), which it placed in a free zone.</seg>
<seg id="138">Subsequently, the company transferred ownership of the goods to a Swiss company, for a value of USD 14 400 (unit price USD 25/piece) and the goods were exported back to SR.</seg>
<seg id="139">The goods were not unloaded in the Czech Republic, but left the free zone area on the same means of transport.</seg>
<seg id="140">The Slovak tax administration has initiated tax inspections of individual tax years 2004 and 2005 with the supplier of goods on suspicion of carousel transactions.</seg>
<seg id="141">The verification of the underlying transactions was requested from the Czech locally competent tax authorities via several SCAC forms.</seg>
<seg id="142">Individual responses gradually built up a picture of the shops and confirmed the involvement of stakeholders from the Slovak Republic and the Czech Republic in the carousel shops.</seg>
<seg id="143">The SAO, the Czech Republic, in cooperation with the SAO of the Slovak Republic, found that in these trade relations there was a deliberate gradual decrease in the value of the goods.</seg>
<seg id="144">On the basis of the information gathered, the SR Tax Directorate concluded that in this case of carousel trade there is free pricing (i.e. the importation of undervalued goods and its overestimation by domestic companies in the importer-exporter chain) which is not an infringement of the VAT Act in the SR.</seg>
<seg id="145">Under current legislation, the payment of excess VAT to export companies cannot be avoided as they fulfil all the conditions of the Act to exempt supplies from VAT.</seg>
<seg id="146">o</seg>
<seg id="147">The Czech taxpayer had his VAT registration revoked on 12 July 2005.</seg>
<seg id="148">On 27 October 2005, following a voluntary application for VAT registration, that body became taxable again.</seg>
<seg id="149">The Czech taxpayer entered into the DAP for the month of 8/2005 (i.e. the period when he was not subject to VAT) the value of the acquisition of goods (a printing press) from SR amounting to CZK 1,174,000 and claimed the right to deduct VAT.</seg>
<seg id="150">This value corresponded to a supply of goods from a Slovak payer amounting to 1 530 thousand Sk, which the Slovak payer listed in the DAP as a supply of goods to another EU Member State with a right to deduct VAT.</seg>
<seg id="151">The Slovak tax administrator asked to verify the said delivery using the SCAC form because the Slovak supplier had not shown how he acquired the goods delivered to the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="152">The SAO, Czech Republic found that the Czech payer did not cooperate with the tax administration and did not reside at the address listed in the Commercial Register.</seg>
<seg id="153">As part of the international exchange of information, a local investigation will be carried out in the Czech Republic by the locally competent tax authority to examine the data.</seg>
<seg id="154">o</seg>
<seg id="155">The Slovak payer reported in the recapitulative statement for Q3 2004 supplies of goods worth 956K. Sk tax entity from the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="156">The Czech entity's VAT number was marked as erroneous by VIES.</seg>
<seg id="157">A check in the payers' database revealed that such a TIN was never allocated in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="158">According to invoices issued by the Slovak payer, it was the execution of electro-fitting works on real estate in the Czech Republic, not the delivery of goods from SR to the Czech Republic, but the provision of services.</seg>
<seg id="159">The services were invoiced without VAT as the Czech entity told the Slovak entity that it was registered as a VAT payer in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="160">The Slovak tax administration requested to verify the facts by using the SCAC form.</seg>
<seg id="161">The SAO, the Czech Republic, by enquiry with the local tax administration in the Czech Republic, found that the tax entity named on the invoices as a customer was never registered as a VAT payer in the Czech Republic, did not declare the tax on the services received from the Slovak entity and did not declare the tax on the acquisition of goods.</seg>
<seg id="162">There was no local investigation or tax check with the Czech entity, its current whereabouts are unknown.</seg>
<seg id="163">On the basis of an international exchange of information, the Czech tax authorities learned that the Czech taxpayer had become a taxpayer of VAT by law by accepting the service.</seg>
<seg id="164">The Slovak tax entity will be subject to a tax audit for the first to fourth quarters of 2004.</seg>
<seg id="165">o</seg>
<seg id="166">The Slovak payer reported in the recapitulative statement for Q3 2004 the delivery of goods worth CZK 1,055,000. Sk to the Czech payer.</seg>
<seg id="167">According to invoices issued by the Slovak payer, it was the execution of electro-fitting works on real estate in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="168">This was not a supply of goods from SR to the Czech Republic, but a supply of services.</seg>
<seg id="169">The Slovak tax administration requested to verify the facts by using the SCAC form.</seg>
<seg id="170">The SAO, the Czech Republic, enquired at the local tax administration in the Czech Republic, found that the Czech entity was a VAT payer at the time of the supply and that a local investigation was carried out on it to verify the acquisition of goods from other EU Member States in the 3rd quarter of 2004.</seg>
<seg id="171">On the basis of this local investigation, it was found that the present case was not really an acquisition of goods but an acquisition of services, which was also reported by the Czech entity in a proper DAP.</seg>
<seg id="172">Furthermore, the tax office found that the Czech operator had not paid VAT at the correct amount for the tax period of Q3 2004 as a result of a bad procedure in the calculation of VAT.</seg>
<seg id="173">The tax entity shall submit an additional DAP.</seg>
<seg id="174">The SAO SR enquired at the local competent tax office and found that the Slovak payer had misstated the provision of the service in the recapitulative statement and would be subject to a tax audit for the 1st to 4th quarters of 2004.</seg>
<seg id="175">o</seg>
<seg id="176">The Czech tax entity has voluntarily registered as a VAT payer since 10 March 2004.</seg>
<seg id="177">For Q1 2004, DAP reported high turnover on both inputs and outputs.</seg>
<seg id="178">The locally competent tax administration initiated the tax procedure, the subject did not cooperate with the tax administration, so he was assessed VAT of 0 CZK due to suspicion of involvement in the carousel business.</seg>
