<seg id="364">During the same period, DR CLO accepted a total of 71 ZhOI and 7 SPI from the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="365">Of the 71 RUs accepted, 64 (i.e. 90.1%) were discharged within the stipulated time limit of 3 months, 5 (i.e. 7.0%) were discharged after this time limit (for the remaining 2 cases, no discharge deadline could be determined from the material transmitted).</seg>
<seg id="366">More detailed data on the time taken to process YES received by MF CLOs and DR CLOs are given in the following graph.</seg>
<seg id="367">Reasons for sending an APO, as stated on SCAC forms, are given in the following table.</seg>
<seg id="368">Conclusion</seg>
<seg id="369">Compliance with Council Regulation (EC) No 1798/2003 on administrative cooperation in the field of VAT, as well as the use of the VIES system to exchange information between EU Member States, in particular to monitor the exercise of the right to VAT exemption, has been tested on the basis of international cooperation.</seg>
<seg id="370">International cooperation made it possible to examine selected intra-Community transactions between VAT payers from the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="371">An examination of the selected transactions revealed that, on the basis of an international exchange of information, the tax administrations of the two countries had detected cases of companies making fictitious intra-Community commercial transactions to obtain excess VAT deductions, as well as cases where the purchasers had failed to declare the correct amount of VAT on supplies received.</seg>
<seg id="372">Furthermore, the audit found differences in the processing and use of VIES data by the tax administrations of the two countries.</seg>
<seg id="373">The audit also highlighted problems caused by different reporting of intra-Community supplies and acquisitions data across EU Member States.</seg>
<seg id="374">The harmonisation of the conditions for reporting such data within the EU would lead to streamlining of the control activities of national tax administrations.</seg>
<seg id="375">Examination of the VAT administration and use of the VIES system by the financial and tax authorities revealed that the VIES system was not sufficiently used by all VIES options and the relevant statutory authorisations.</seg>
<seg id="376">Furthermore, it was found that the VIES system did not in all cases provide up-to-date information on deliveries of goods and on the validity of taxable persons' VAT registration.</seg>
<seg id="377">The SAO SR compared the data on the occurrence of erroneous data in the SH, processed before the start of the inspection, with the data processed after the completion of the inspection.</seg>
<seg id="378">From the comparison of these data, it was clear that the SAO audit of SR had an effect not only on reducing the number of IA with erroneously reported TIN, but also on reducing the number of unrepaired errors in the SH.</seg>
<seg id="379">In case of discrepancies in the reported data, the SAO asked the tax authorities to carry out local investigations or to carry out tax checks.</seg>
<seg id="380">The SAO, Czech Republic did not have such an option under the current legislation in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="381">The lessons learned from the audit action showed that VIES provided tax administrations with the basic information necessary to check the correct application of VAT in intra-Community transactions.</seg>
<seg id="382">As there continues to be scope for tax evasion in this area, increased attention needs to be paid to intra-community transactions when managing VAT.</seg>
<seg id="383">Communiqué</seg>
<seg id="384">This report was prepared in Czech, English and Slovak languages and signed by the President of the Supreme Audit Office, the Czech Republic and the President of the Najvyššie Audit Office of the Slovak Republic.</seg>
</p>
