<p>
<seg id="1">Parallel control of the administration of value added tax and excise duties between the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic</seg>
<seg id="2">Introduction Word</seg>
<seg id="3">This information material provides an overview of the progress and results of parallel control actions carried out by the Supreme Audit Office and the Supreme Audit Office of the Slovak Republic, which focused on the area of administration based on added value and excise duties.</seg>
<seg id="4">Cooperation between the supreme audit institutions of the two countries was carried out on the basis of the control cooperation agreement concluded in February 2004.</seg>
<seg id="5">The theme of the parallel control actions was chosen in view of the fact that indirect taxes contribute significantly to the revenue of the national budgets of both countries.</seg>
<seg id="6">The design of value added tax, allowing the refund of excess deduction, provides scope for tax fraud or evasion.</seg>
<seg id="7">High rates of excise duty, particularly on tobacco and tobacco products, ethyl alcohol and mineral oils, mean high profits for those who escape taxation by illegally selling these goods.</seg>
<seg id="8">Tax fraud is a problem not only in the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic, but also in other countries of the European Union.</seg>
<seg id="9">Given the need to address this issue comprehensively across the European Union, the VAT Working Group has been set up by the supreme audit institutions of the Member States of the European Union, with both countries' highest audit offices actively involved.</seg>
<seg id="10">The greatest benefits of the control actions undertaken can be seen not only in the exchange of experience, but in particular in the joint effort to identify problem areas of indirect tax management in order to reduce the scope for tax evasion.</seg>
<seg id="11">The experience and knowledge gained will be used in the framework of planned indirect tax controls, mainly aimed at involving the tax administrations of the two States in the VIES system, which allows the movement of goods between the Member States of the European Union to be controlled.</seg>
<seg id="12">Report on the results of the Value Added Tax and Excise Administration Review for 2002 and 2003</seg>
<seg id="13">1. Introduction</seg>
<seg id="14">Control number: (CZ) 04/07 (SK) 18/2004</seg>
<seg id="15">Object of control:</seg>
<seg id="16">(CZ) Value added tax and excise duties</seg>
<seg id="17">(SK) Control of the tax administration process for the administration, control and enforcement of value added tax and excise duties</seg>
<seg id="18">On 11.2.2004, the Contract for Cooperation in Audit Activities between the Supreme Audit Office (SAO) and the NajHigher Audit Office of the Slovak Republic (SAO SR) was concluded. The subject of the contract was cooperation in the implementation of parallel control actions "Value Added Tax and Excise Tax," included in the SAO's 2004 audit work plan under No 04/07, and "Control of the management process of dane pri administration, control and recovery of taxes on prized value and rebrebrebrebate taxes," included in SAO SR's audit work plan under No 18/2004.</seg>
<seg id="19">The cooperation consisted of exchanging information to the extent provided for in the contract and producing a joint final report on the outcome of the checks.</seg>
<seg id="20">Both parties undertook in the contract to provide each other with information from public sources, from the customs administration database and from the tax files kept by the tax authorities in the Czech Republic and the tax authorities in the Slovak Republic, which the contracting parties could not obtain when checking the application of value added tax and excise duties on imports and exports from sources in the territory of the relevant State.</seg>
<seg id="21">The checks were carried out in parallel between January and August 2004.</seg>
<seg id="22">In the territory of the Czech Republic (hereinafter referred to as the Czech Republic), the control was carried out by the State Budget Department and the territorial departments of southern Bohemia, northeastern Bohemia, southern Moravia, central Moravia and northern Moravia.</seg>
<seg id="23">The audited persons were the General Directorate of Customs and 12 selected financial offices: the Tax Office for Prague 1, the Tax Office for Prague 3, the Tax Office in Český Budějovice, the Tax Office in Frýdek-Místek, the Tax Office in Hodonin, the Tax Office in Jihlava, the Tax Office in Kostelec nad Orlicí, the Tax Office in Kroměříž, the Tax Office in Písek, the Tax Office in Rožnov pod Radhoštěm, the Financial Office in Ústí nad Orlicí, the Financial Office in Velký Meziříčí.</seg>
<seg id="24">The audit on the territory of the Slovak Republic (hereinafter referred to as ‘SR’) was carried out by the Tax and Customs Division of the SAO SR in cooperation with the SAO Expozituras SR Banská Bystrica and Košice on 10 selected tax offices:</seg>
<seg id="25">Bratislava Tax Office pre Selected Tax Entities, Bratislava Tax Office III, Trnava Tax Office, Pú-chov Tax Office, Banská Bystrica Tax Office I, Liptovský Mikuláš Tax Office, Žilina Tax Office I, Žilina II Tax Office, Košice Tax Office I and Košice Tax Office IV.</seg>
<seg id="26">Target of control</seg>
<seg id="27">The aim of the control actions was to examine the fulfilment of the obligations of financial and tax authorities and customs authorities in the administration of value added tax and excise duties, with a focus on the collection of such taxes on the import and export of goods and services.</seg>
<seg id="28">The aim of international cooperation was to verify imports and exports of selected commodities between the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic in the Customs Database and the Customs Database of the Slovak Republic and to verify them in tax returns at the relevant financial and tax offices respectively.</seg>
<seg id="29">The audited period was 2002 and 2003.</seg>
<seg id="30">2. Review of control results</seg>
<seg id="31">2.1. General evaluation of control activities</seg>
<seg id="32">In the framework of the international cooperation of the SAO, the SAO of the Czech Republic transmitted from the Customs Database 22 206 items of the Uniform Customs Declarations (hereinafter referred to as "JCD") on imports and exports of goods between the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic, and vice versa, the SAO of the Slovak Republic forwarded 30 221 items of the JCD to the SAO of the Customs Database of the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="33">A comparison was made between the printed JCD items from the Customs database of the Czech Republic and the Customs database of the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="34">Out of 5,883 selected JCD items from the CR Customs Database, a total of 43% of related JCD items were assigned.</seg>
<seg id="35">Out of the 12,343 selected JCD entries from the SR customs database, a total of 26% of the related JCD entries were assigned.</seg>
<seg id="36">On the basis of the unassigned JCD entries, a selection of the files of the tax entities was made at the financial and tax offices, where the declared imports and exports were further verified in cooperation with the customs administrations of the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="37">Based on the exchange of information from the documents of the customs administrations of the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic and the financial and tax authorities respectively, the implementation of the reported imports and exports between the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic was verified in the territory of the second state.</seg>
<seg id="38">The SAO and SAO SR carried out a joint pilot inspection at the Starý Hrozenkov - Drietoma border customs crossing, in which both parties cooperated closely in verifying the accuracy of data on the movement of goods between the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="39">The audit did not identify any deficiencies in the record of selected cases of imports and exports of goods made in 2002.</seg>
<seg id="40">International cooperation has made it possible to examine trade transactions made between trading partners from both countries and has highlighted deficiencies in the record of imports and exports.</seg>
<seg id="41">2.2. Summary of control results</seg>
<seg id="42">The audit of the SAO and SAO of the Slovak Republic focused on imports and exports of spirit and spirits, tobacco and tobacco products, computers and computer components, mobile phones and their components, as well as other types of goods, in the field of international cooperation.</seg>
<seg id="43">On the basis of a check of the files of tax entities at selected financial and tax offices, the SAO asked for verification of the execution of exports of goods declared on 40 JCDs for a total statistical value of 15,301,093 CZK and the SAO SR for verification of exports for a statistical value of 56,989 Sk.</seg>
<seg id="44">Among other things, the SAO and SAO SR found the following:</seg>
<seg id="45">- the commercial transactions were not declared in the same way on both sides, making it difficult to identify the corresponding imports and exports in the Customs Database of the Czech Republic and the Customs Database of the Slovak Republic,</seg>
<seg id="46">- errors in the entry of data into customs databases made it impossible to identify certain imports or exports,</seg>
<seg id="47">- there has been no evidence of corresponding imports into the SR for some Czech exports.</seg>
<seg id="48">In such cases, there is a reasonable suspicion of fictitious exports of goods for the purpose of improperly claiming value added tax deductions;</seg>
<seg id="49">- Tax entities failed to comply with some of the statutory obligations in reporting imports and exports on value added tax returns;</seg>
<seg id="50">- shortcomings have been identified in the work of the financial and/or tax offices in the administration of value added tax and excise duties and in their interaction with customs offices.</seg>
<seg id="51">In the field of value added tax and excise duties, international trade will continue to need attention in order to effectively minimise tax evasion.</seg>
<seg id="52">In particular, it is important to improve the activity of tax administrations in the administration of value added tax.</seg>
<seg id="53">The basis for effective control of excise duties is the control of document circulation, systematic physical control of goods and mutual exchange of information on the import and export of goods.</seg>
<seg id="54">3. Description of the value added tax and excise tax situation</seg>
<seg id="55">Value Added Tax</seg>
<seg id="56">Value added tax (‘VAT’) was levied by the tax and tax authorities on taxable transactions effected within the country and by the customs authorities on importation of the goods.</seg>
<seg id="57">The revenue from the tax was due to the difference between the tax liability collected and the excess VAT refunded in the case of the tax authorities.</seg>
<seg id="58">The VAT revenue at the customs offices was determined by the amount of tax they collected.</seg>
<seg id="59">The tax collected by the customs authorities was reflected, in accordance with the basic principles of the VAT mechanism, in the tax deductions applied to the financial and tax authorities respectively.</seg>
<seg id="60">For most financial and tax authorities, excess VAT deductions exceeded tax liability.</seg>
<seg id="61">VAT is one of the flagship taxes in terms of state budget revenue, as it accounted for about 31% of the tax revenue of the state budget of the Czech Republic in 2003 and approximately 42% of the tax revenue of the state budget of the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="62">The total VAT collection in the Czech Republic amounted to CZK 162.9 billion in 2003.</seg>
<seg id="63">The tax and customs authorities collected a total of CZK 394.3 billion in VAT in 2003 and the excess VAT refunds totalled CZK 231.4 billion.</seg>
<seg id="64">The total VAT collection in SR in 2003 amounted to 83.8 bn Sk.</seg>
<seg id="65">Tax and customs authorities collected 187.0 billion in VAT in 2003, and refunded excess VAT totalled 103.2 billion Sk.</seg>
<seg id="66">Excise duties</seg>
<seg id="67">The collection of excise duties (‘SpD’) was carried out by the competent financial and tax authorities and, on importation, by customs authorities of products subject to SpD.</seg>
<seg id="68">The share of SpD in the tax revenues of the state budget in the Czech Republic was about 16% in 2003 and about 19% in SR.</seg>
<seg id="69">The total collection of SpDs collected in the Czech Republic by financial and customs authorities in 2003 amounted to 85.6 billion CZK and in the Slovak Republic amounted to 38.0 billion CZK.</seg>
<seg id="70">4. Control Action Progress</seg>
<seg id="71">The cooperation between the SAO and SAO SR took place in two stages.</seg>
<seg id="72">In the first stage, a comparison of imports and exports of selected commodities from the customs databases of the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic was made; in the second stage, the results of this comparison were used in the mutual verification of the implementation of selected trade transactions between the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic and in the checks carried out on the territory of the two states.</seg>
<seg id="73">4.1.</seg>
<seg id="74">Preparation of control action</seg>
<seg id="75">The first proposal for cooperation on parallel VAT and SpD controls was presented at a working meeting of SAO and SAO SR representatives in April 2003.</seg>
<seg id="76">In November 2003, a coordination meeting was held at which, among other things, a selection of commodities was agreed - goods which posed a significant risk in complying with customs and tax legislation: - ethyl alcohol, tariff headings 2207 and 2208, - tobacco and tobacco products, tariff headings 2401, 2402 and 2403, - computers and computer components, tariff headings 8471 and 8473 30, - mobile phones and their accessories, tariff subheadings 8525 20 91, 8525 20 99, 8529 90 40.</seg>
<seg id="77">The two parties agreed that the selection of tax entities for inspection will be made: (a) from unallocated items identified by comparing exports and imports of selected commodities between the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic; (b) from entities carrying out imports and exports regularly or on a one-off basis in large volumes; (c) on the basis of findings from inspections carried out by selected tax and financial authorities.</seg>
<seg id="78">4.2. Comparison of Customs Databases of the Czech Republic and Slovak Republic</seg>
<seg id="79">In the first stage, the mutual attribution mechanism of JCD items registered in the Customs Databases of the Czech Republic and Slovak Republic was tested on a sample of imports and exports of selected commodities for the month of October 2002.</seg>
<seg id="80">Subsequently, a proportion of exports from the Czech Republic were compared with imports into the Slovak Republic for 2002 and vice versa for selected commodities according to the Customs Tariff:</seg>
<seg id="81">- 2207 Undenatured ethyl alcohol of an alcoholic strength by volume of 80% vol or higher; Ethyl alcohol and other spirits denatured, of any strength,</seg>
<seg id="82">- 2208 Undenatured ethyl alcohol of an alcoholic strength by volume of less than 80% vol; spirits, liqueurs and other spirituous beverages,</seg>
<seg id="83">- 2401 Unmanufactured tobacco; tobacco waste,</seg>
<seg id="84">- 2402 Cigars (whether or not with their ends cut off), cigars (cigarillos) and cigarettes made of tobacco or tobacco substitutes,</seg>
<seg id="85">- 2403 Other tobacco products and tobacco substitutes; homogenised or reconstituted tobacco; tobacco extracts and punishments (essences);</seg>
<seg id="86">- 8525 20 91 Transmission apparatus containing reception equipment: For cellular network (mobile phones),</seg>
<seg id="87">- 8525 20 99 Transmission apparatus incorporating reception equipment: Other,</seg>
<seg id="88">- 8529 90 40 Parts suitable for use solely or principally with the apparatus of headings 8525 to 8528.</seg>
<seg id="89">Other: Parts of apparatus falling in subheadings 8525 10 50, 8525 20 91, 8525 20 99, 8525 40 11 and 8527 90 92.</seg>
<seg id="90">The JCD entries from the Customs databases of the Czech Republic and Slovak Republic were attributed to each other based on the conformity of the individual paragraphs of the JCD (e.g. invoiced price, quantity, weight, registration number of the vehicle carrying the cargo, date of crossing the national border, tariff heading, etc.).</seg>
<seg id="91">The results of the comparison are presented in the following tables and graphs.</seg>
<seg id="92">The cross-attribution of individual imports and exports was hampered by, among other things, the fact that trade transactions were not declared in the same way on both sides.</seg>
<seg id="93">For example, an export from the Czech Republic declared on one export JCD was declared on the territory of SR for multiple import JCD, or the export JCD had a different number of items from the import JCD.</seg>
<seg id="94">Other factors influencing the success of the attribution were the different composition of data in the customs databases of the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic, as well as the time shift between the registration of exports in the customs database of one country and the registration of corresponding imports in the customs database of another.</seg>
<seg id="95">The results of the comparison were used in the selection of control samples at the audited financial and tax offices respectively.</seg>
<seg id="96">Priority was given to certain tax entities that carried out imports/exports between the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic, which could not be identified in both databases.</seg>
<seg id="97">In addition, certain tax entities for which data on imports/exports between the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic were found in both databases were selected for the verification of the transactions reported on VAT returns.</seg>
<seg id="98">4.3. Pilot check at Starý Hrozenkov-Drietoma border customs crossing</seg>
<seg id="99">The border customs crossing for the performance of the pilot inspection was selected on the basis of a joint analysis of unassigned JCD items in the customs databases of the CR and SR.</seg>
<seg id="100">Pursuant to a bilateral agreement between the Customs Authorities of the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic, the use of control sheets has been introduced at border customs crossing points between the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic since 1 June 1998.</seg>
<seg id="101">The aim of this measure was to eliminate customs and tax evasion as far as possible, to provide an overview of the movement of means of transport transporting goods of a commercial nature within the customs area and to create the conditions for comparing customs registers with each other.</seg>
<seg id="102">The joint pilot inspection was carried out from 8.3.2004 to 26.3.2004 and aimed at examining this system of customs control.</seg>
<seg id="103">Procedure for the use of control sheets at the Starý Hrozenkov-Drietoma border customs crossing:</seg>
<seg id="104">1. Considering the vehicle, issuing a checklist and handing it to the driver.</seg>
<seg id="105">2) Unloading the vehicle in the designated sector in the parking lot.</seg>
<seg id="106">Customs discussions in the check-in hall of the Policia ČR, Policie SR, Customs Administration of the Czech Republic, Customs Administration of the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="107">The check-in process was confirmed by each component stamping the control sheet.</seg>
<seg id="108">3) Bringing the vehicle into the physical inspection area.</seg>
<seg id="109">Presentation of the control sheet, JCD, or other documents, as appropriate, to the customs officer - check that all prescribed acts and documents have been carried out.</seg>
<seg id="110">Execution of physical checks by relevant files.</seg>
<seg id="111">Releasing the vehicle from customs.</seg>
<seg id="112">Posru: When importing goods into the Czech Republic, the weighing vehicles were carried out directly by the Customs Administration of the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="113">When the goods were imported into SR, the vehicles weighed were carried out by the staff of the authorised legal entity.</seg>
<seg id="114">The vehicles were then entered into a computerised record.</seg>
<seg id="115">4.3.1 Control sample</seg>
<seg id="116">Exports from the Czech Republic to the Slovak Republic</seg>
<seg id="117">The control sample was selected on the basis of an analysis of records from the Customs Exports Database of the Czech Republic in 2002.</seg>
<seg id="118">The composition of the control sample for exports is given in Table 4.</seg>
<seg id="119">4.3.2. Control sheets and their records Exports from the Czech Republic to the Slovak Republic</seg>
<seg id="120">When exported from the Czech Republic to the Slovak Republic, the certificates of inspection were issued and registered by the Customs Administration of the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="121">The Customs Administration of the Czech Republic recorded the registration numbers of these control sheets in an electronic database of exports.</seg>
<seg id="122">Out of 453 JCD entries, the SAO SR tracked 256 cases of imports into the Slovak Republic, according to data from the Customs database of the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic. The remaining 197 JCD items were identified by the SAO of the Slovak Republic in cooperation with the workers of the Drietoma border customs crossing.</seg>
<seg id="123">Exports from SR to CR</seg>
<seg id="124">On export from SR to the Czech Republic, the control sheets were issued and registered by the Customs Administration of the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="125">Out of a total of 339 JCD entries of the selected control sample, the SAO in cooperation with border customs crossing staff, Starý Hrozenkov assigned to 295 JCD entries the corresponding registration numbers of the control sheets.</seg>
<seg id="126">The other 44 cases were identified in their records by the border customs checkpoint staff at Drietoma and the export of goods from SR to the Czech Republic was confirmed.</seg>
<seg id="127">The SAO and SAO SR audit did not find deficiencies in the registration of selected cases of imports and exports of goods in 2002 at the Old Hrozenkov-Drietoma border customs crossing.</seg>
<seg id="128">4.4. Selected control findings when verifying business transactions</seg>
<seg id="129">In the framework of international cooperation, the realisation of imports and exports between the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic was verified from the supporting documents of customs administrations and financial and tax offices in the territory of the second state.</seg>
<seg id="130">The following were verified for selected tax entities:</seg>
<seg id="131">- whether the submitted JCD were registered in the customs databases of the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic,</seg>
<seg id="132">- the fulfilment of the legal conditions for the application of the deduction of VAT on importation, the refund of excess VAT and the application of the exemption from VAT on exportation.</seg>
<seg id="133">The verification of the commercial transactions found:</seg>
<seg id="134">1. The SAO of SR requested verification of the implementation of alcohol exports at a statistical value of 56 989 Sk.</seg>
<seg id="135">The SAO identified the corresponding imports in the Czech Customs Database at a statistical value of 42,624 CZK. r</seg>
<seg id="136">2. The photographic equipment and accessories import and export company claimed an excess VAT deduction of CZK 3,740,664 in its VAT return for the month of December 2002.</seg>
<seg id="137">In order to check reported exports from the Czech Republic, the SAO selected 3 JCD (16 items) with a statistical value of 1,274,822 CZK.</seg>
<seg id="138">The SAO of SR identified 3 corresponding import JCD (17 items) at a statistical value of 1,724,321 Sk.</seg>
<seg id="139">VAT was paid in the SR to the competent customs office.</seg>
<seg id="140">3. The company, whose main business was the optical equipment business, applied a total excess VAT deduction in 2002 that was 4,1,36,000 CZK higher than the tax liability.</seg>
<seg id="141">To verify the reported business activity, the SAO selected the export JCD (32 items) at a statistical value of 7,154,124 CZK.</seg>
<seg id="142">The SAO SR found that this JCD corresponds to an import JCD (12 items) with a statistical value of 9,653,827 Sk.</seg>
<seg id="143">VAT was paid in the SR to the competent customs office.</seg>
<seg id="144">4. The company involved in, among other things, the purchase of goods for resale and sale, did not report any exports of goods in the 2002 and 2003 VAT returns filed.</seg>
<seg id="145">According to the Customs database of the Czech Republic, the statistical value of goods exports totalled 3,439,888 CZK in 2002.</seg>
<seg id="146">Based on these facts, the SAO selected for verification 5 export JCD (5 items) for a total statistical value of CZK 669,839.</seg>
<seg id="147">The SAO of SR identified 5 corresponding import JCD (5 items) at a statistical value of 1 012 656 Sk.</seg>
<seg id="148">The audit of the SAO of the Slovak Republic at the competent tax office showed that the declared imports were carried out and VAT paid.</seg>
<seg id="149">5. The company, whose business included the purchase of goods for resale, manufacture, installation and repair of electrical machinery and apparatus, declared exports of goods worth CZK 12,966,706 in VAT returns in 2002.</seg>
<seg id="150">According to the Customs database of the Czech Republic, in 2002 the total value of exports was 14,474,381 CZK.</seg>
<seg id="151">The SAO submitted 17 export JCDs (59 items) for a total statistical value of 2,975,122 CZK.</seg>
<seg id="152">The SAO SR identified 13 JCD (50 items) in the SR Customs Database, with a statistical value of 3 621 370 Sk.</seg>
<seg id="153">The SR Customs Database failed to identify the corresponding import JCD to 4 export JCD (9 items) totalling a statistical value of 399,776 CZK.</seg>
<seg id="154">The relevant tax office in SR verified these imports with the taxpayer.</seg>
<seg id="155">The tax entity, listed on the JCD as an importer into SR, commented in the minutes of the local investigation that it had not carried out the imports declared on the Czech export JCD.</seg>
<seg id="156">The SAO of SR therefore asked the local competent tax office to carry out a VAT and corporation tax audit for the tax years 2002 and 2003.</seg>
<seg id="157">6. A company involved in the import and sale of cigarettes exported tobacco stickers worth CZK 7,338,199 in 2002 and CZK 12,228,545 in 2003, according to the Customs Database of the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="158">In its VAT returns, the company reported no exports in 2002 and 2003.</seg>
<seg id="159">The SAO selected for verification 5 export JCD (5 items) totalling a statistical value of 2,471,598 CZK.</seg>
<seg id="160">For 4 export JCD (4 items) in a total statistical value of 2,246,860 CZK, the SAO SR identified 7 JCD (7 items) in a statistical value of 2,919,514 Sk in the Customs Database SR.</seg>
<seg id="161">A corresponding import could not be attributed to the export JCD (1 item) in statistical value of CZK 224,738 in the SR customs database.</seg>
<seg id="162">7. The software delivery company did not report goods exports in its 2002 and 2003 VAT returns.</seg>
<seg id="163">According to the Customs database of the Czech Republic, the statistical value of goods exports in 2002 and 2003 totalled 1,630,198 CZK.</seg>
<seg id="164">The SAO selected 9 JCD (9 items) for verification in SR, with a total statistical value of CZK 755,588.</seg>
<seg id="165">In the Customs Database SR, the SAO identified 8 JCD (8 items) in statistical value 915 601 Sk.</seg>
<seg id="166">The export JCD (1 item) with a statistical value of £68,286 could not be attributed to the corresponding import in the SR customs database.</seg>
<seg id="167">In those cases, it was not possible to identify in the SR customs database the corresponding imports to 6 JCD with a statistical value of 692,800 CZK.</seg>
<seg id="168">Of which:</seg>
<seg id="169">- 2 export JCD from the CR Customs Database at a statistical value of 293,024 CZK, the SR Customs Database failed to identify the corresponding import JCD (see paragraphs 6 and 7).</seg>
<seg id="170">Due to a certain error rate in the entry of data into the customs database, it was not possible to identify some of the registered imports, e.g. in cases where the name of the importer was missing or there was an error in the tax identification number (TIN).</seg>
<seg id="171">It can therefore not be established with certainty that those exports did not take place.</seg>
<seg id="172">- 4 export JCDs from the Customs database of the Czech Republic were not shown to have imports corresponding to exports from the Czech Republic to the Slovak Republic at a statistical value of 399,776 CZK (see point 5).</seg>
<seg id="173">In such cases, there is a reasonable suspicion of the fictitious export of the goods for the purpose of improperly claiming the VAT deduction.</seg>
<seg id="174">5. Control of imports and exports of goods and services within the control of selected financial and tax authorities</seg>
<seg id="175">5.1. Check pattern</seg>
<seg id="176">In order to verify the fulfilment of the obligations of taxable persons in respect of imports and exports of goods and services and to evaluate the level of cooperation between financial and customs authorities, the files of taxable persons have been selected at the audited financial and tax offices, according to the following criteria:</seg>
<seg id="177">1. tax subjects were selected from the customs databases of the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic: (a) with the highest volume of imports, (b) with the highest amount of VAT charged, (c) with the highest volume of exports,</seg>
<seg id="178">(a) the VAT deductions applied on importation; (b) the excess VAT deductions applied; (c) the right to a refund of SpD; (d) the VAT exemption applied on exportation;</seg>
<seg id="179">3. tax entities that have been subject to a tax audit.</seg>
<seg id="180">The sampling was carried out irrespective of the country of destination with a focus on risky commodities.</seg>
<seg id="181">5.2. Checking findings in the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="182">An overview of imports into the Czech Republic and exports from the Czech Republic for risky commodities in 2002 and 2003 is given in the table below:</seg>
<seg id="183">5.2.1. Inspection of selected sample at tax offices</seg>
<seg id="184">The SAO focused on the audited financial authorities in particular on:</seg>
<seg id="185">- the process of the tax authorities in verifying the accuracy of the VAT declared,</seg>
<seg id="186">- the cooperation of the tax authorities with the customs administration,</seg>
<seg id="187">- Comparing data from the customs database with the JCD database at the tax offices with a focus on comparing the declared value, applying the correct VAT rate following the tariff classification of goods or services, or comparing data on JCD and accompanying invoices with data in the customs database,</seg>
<seg id="188">- Comparing data from VAT returns on transactions made and received from abroad with data in the JCD database at tax offices or in the customs database,</seg>
<seg id="189">- how to verify entitlement to VAT exemption when exporting goods or services abroad;</seg>
<seg id="190">- a comparison of the volume of exports of goods or services declared in VAT returns with data from the customs database.</seg>
<seg id="191">The JCD database at the tax offices contained only records of those imports and exports in respect of which the taxpayer was obliged to enter the import or export on a tax return.</seg>
<seg id="192">At the audited tax offices, the files of the tax entities were examined, which reported imports totalling CZK 60,396,379,000 in 2002 and 2003 in the tax returns, with corresponding VAT totalling CZK 12,644,052,000.</seg>
<seg id="193">Furthermore, the files of tax entities reporting exports worth a total of CZK 47,323,111 in tax returns for 2002 and 2003 were checked.</seg>
<seg id="194">According to the Customs Database of the Czech Republic in 2002 and 2003, the tax subjects who were examined for imports and exports between the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic carried out imports into the Czech Republic from the Slovak Republic with a total VAT base of CZK 3,759,352,000, VAT of CZK 767,607,000 and exports from the Czech Republic to the Slovak Republic with a total statistical value of CZK 1,989,090,000.</seg>
<seg id="195">The detected differences between the records in the JCD database at the tax offices and in the Customs database of the Czech Republic were examined as follows:</seg>
<seg id="196">- JCD items that were missing from the CR Customs Database were requested directly from the General Directorate of Customs of the CR,</seg>
<seg id="197">- the JCD items that were missing from the tax authorities' database were verified as not being cancelled documents,</seg>
<seg id="198">- for JCD items where different values were found between the Customs database of the Czech Republic and the Financial Offices database, the relevant JCD was requested from the General Directorate of Customs of the Czech Republic in written form including the accompanying invoices.</seg>
<seg id="199">The examination revealed that the JCD database at the tax offices did not contain, for example, records of import JCDs with a total value of VAT of 3,622,000 CZK and records of export JCDs with a total statistical value of 9,359,000 CZK.</seg>
<seg id="200">5.2.1.1. Differences found</seg>
<seg id="201">A comparison of the JCD database at the tax offices and the accumulated tax liability for 2002 and 2003 in the VAT returns for a selected sample of tax subjects revealed the following differences:</seg>
<seg id="202">The differences in values were mainly due to:</seg>
<seg id="203">- The time lag between the realisation of the imports and the exercise of the right to deduct the VAT charged on the importation of the goods.</seg>
<seg id="204">The taxpayer could exercise the right to deduct on importation of the goods within three years of the end of the tax year in which the goods were placed under the relevant scheme or, in the case of the temporary importation scheme, within three years of the end of the tax year in which the scheme came to an end.</seg>
<seg id="205">- The time lag between the export performance and the time when the taxpayer received the JCD.</seg>
<seg id="206">The taxable person was required to enter the details of the exports effected, exempt from the obligation to apply output tax, in the VAT return at the earliest for the tax year in which the goods left the country, if he also had the tax document that was JCD.</seg>
<seg id="207">- Failure to comply with the obligations of taxable persons when reporting imports and exports on VAT returns.</seg>
<seg id="208">In some cases, the taxpayer did not enter the correct import and export details in the VAT returns.</seg>
<seg id="209">Since tax entities did not have to attach JCD lists to filed VAT returns, it was made more difficult for tax authorities to control the right to deduct VAT or VAT exemption.</seg>
<seg id="210">5.2.2. Synergies between financial and customs authorities</seg>
<seg id="211">During the period under scrutiny, import or export duties and VAT were repaid or remitted as a result of decisions taken by the customs authorities.</seg>
<seg id="212">The taxpayer was required by law to reduce the previously claimed right to deduct VAT by the amount of tax refunded by the customs office, in the tax return for the period in which the tax was refunded.</seg>
<seg id="213">No legislation provided for the sending of information on changes in the amount of duty and VAT from customs offices to tax offices.</seg>
<seg id="214">Some audited tax authorities received this information, but irregularly or with significant delays, and only from some customs offices.</seg>
<seg id="215">One audited IRS did not receive this information at all.</seg>
<seg id="216">If the tax office did not receive information on changes in the amount of duty and VAT directly from the customs office, it did not have the data needed to check that the legal obligation on tax subjects was fulfilled.</seg>
<seg id="217">In 2002, customs refunded VAT of more than CZK 319 million and in 2003 of more than CZK 398 million.</seg>
<seg id="218">The results of the inspection pointed to persistent weaknesses in the activities of the tax authorities, some systemic errors in the cooperation of the tax authorities with the customs authorities and the failure of some of the obligations of the payers filing VAT returns and SpD.</seg>
<seg id="219">Shortcomings in VAT and SpD management were identified in particular in the following areas:</seg>
<seg id="220">(a) on the cancellation of VAT registrations, the taxable person's obligation to pay VAT on the business property registered or to be registered on the date of the cancellation of the registration in respect of which the taxable person has deducted VAT has been verified only in isolated cases;</seg>
<seg id="221">(b) the tax authorities have not consistently exercised the option to carry out a tax audit or a local investigation.</seg>
<seg id="222">This has in some cases led to inadequate verification of the legitimacy of the right to deduct VAT,</seg>
<seg id="223">(c) official records and minutes of oral proceedings did not contain all the necessary particulars proving that the excess VAT claimed was justified;</seg>
<seg id="224">(d) the tax authorities did not sufficiently verify the imports and exports declared in the VAT returns.</seg>
<seg id="225">5.3. SR control findings</seg>
<seg id="226">5.3.1. Inspection of selected sample at tax offices</seg>
<seg id="227">For the selected sample, the SAO audited or the tax office carried out a tax audit for the tax years 2002 and 2003.</seg>
<seg id="228">After analysing the submitted tax returns and refund claims with the selected tax entities, the SAO of SR requested the tax office to secure the relevant JCDs showing import and export, invoices and proof of payment of tax.</seg>
<seg id="229">Subsequently, the SAO SR checked whether the submitted JCD was registered in the customs database of imports and exports and the fulfilment of the decisive facts and legal conditions in the application of the deduction of input tax on imports, in the refund of excess VAT, in the application of the exemption from export tax and in the refund of SpD.</seg>
<seg id="230">The SAO SR at 10 audited tax offices verified selected cases of imports and exports of goods between the SAR and the Czech Republic in the structure according to the number of JCD items and the sum of statistical values shown in the table below.</seg>
<seg id="231">In total, imports were checked at a statistical value of 856.2 M. Sk, representing 5.11% of the total value of imports of selected commodities from the Czech Republic to the SROV.</seg>
<seg id="232">Exports of selected commodities were checked for a total statistical value of 176 million units, representing 6.87% of the total value of exports of selected commodities from the SR to the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="233">In addition, 618 cases of imports of other goods and services (mainly white tech, packaging and software) from EU states to SR were checked for a total statistical value of 532.8 M. Sk.</seg>
<seg id="234">5.3.2. Synergies between tax and customs</seg>
<seg id="235">The SAO SR's audit of tax offices found discrepancies between the data registered in the Customs Database of the Slovak Republic and the data reported in specific VAT returns, e.g.:</seg>
<seg id="236">- 2 tax subjects (natural persons) declared in their tax returns imports of goods totalling 1 589 261 Sk, on the basis of which they claimed a refund of excess VAT deductions.</seg>
<seg id="237">In local investigations carried out at the instigation of the SAO of the Slovak Republic, tax subjects failed to prove to the Tax Office the validity of the application of input tax by the relevant documents of the realisation of the imports and the payment of VAT,</seg>
<seg id="238">- the tax entity (s.r.o.) declared in its tax return for the January 2003 tax year the taxable transaction received in the value of 77 167 576 Sk, the export of goods in the value of 18 006 041 Sk, and claimed an excess VAT deduction of 17 157 101 Sk.</seg>
<seg id="239">The VAT returns filed for 2003 show that the difference between the volume of purchases and exports of 59 161 535 Sk, which arose in January 2003, was not compensated during the whole of 2003.</seg>
<seg id="240">In the above cases, the SAO requested the competent tax authorities to carry out a tax audit of the excess VAT deductions applied.</seg>
<seg id="241">- in another case, the tax entity (s.r.o.) for the tax year January to June 2002 declared exports of goods worth a total of 87,199 Sk in VAT returns.</seg>
<seg id="242">A verification in the SR customs database revealed that the taxpayer had exported a statistical value of 296 747 Sk. during that period.</seg>
<seg id="243">The Tax Office carried out multiple local investigations at the company's headquarters, finding that the company's manager (a UK citizen) had travelled and the company had left the rented premises without terminating the lease in August 2002.</seg>
<seg id="244">At the time of the audit of the SAO, the tax administration filed a report to the law enforcement authorities on the suspicion of a crime of non-payment of tax.</seg>
<seg id="245">Based on the results of the audit at selected tax offices, the SAO finds that the biggest problems in the administration and control of VAT and SpD were mainly in the following areas:</seg>
<seg id="246">- non-use of the option to carry out a VAT tax check on problematic tax entities, in particular in cases where a high value of excess VAT is applied;</seg>
<seg id="247">- Tax control protocols did not include an inventory of the documents checked</seg>
<seg id="248">- JCD on the import and export of goods,</seg>
<seg id="249">- Insufficient verification of declared imports and exports of goods in tax returns;</seg>
<seg id="250">- the lengthy procedure for tax administrations to make decisions, in particular in the context of the assessment procedure, even with the consequence of forfeiting the right to impose penalties;</seg>
<seg id="251">- Failure to comply with legal conditions when granting tax deferrals;</seg>
<seg id="252">- non-recovery of VAT arrears within the VAT excess refund deadline;</seg>
<seg id="253">- underutilisation of all forms of security and recovery of tax arrears.</seg>
<seg id="254">Based on the audit of the observed shortcomings, the SAO of the Slovak Republic asked the competent tax authorities to carry out a VAT tax audit focusing on the legitimacy of the claimed excess VAT deductions of 14 tax entities.</seg>
<seg id="255">Measures have been taken at all audited tax offices to remedy the weaknesses identified, the implementation of which will be monitored and checked by the SAO.</seg>
<seg id="256">6. Conclusion</seg>
<seg id="257">International cooperation has made it possible to examine trade transactions made between trading partners from both countries and has highlighted deficiencies in the record of imports and exports.</seg>
<seg id="258">Furthermore, the inspections resulted in the detection of persistent deficiencies in the compliance of VAT payers and SpD, in the activity of the financial and tax authorities respectively, in the system of cooperation and exchange of information between tax and customs administrations, which ultimately reduced the efficiency and effectiveness of tax controls.</seg>
<seg id="259">The lessons learned also showed that the tax authorities in the Czech Republic have basic data on imports and exports from the customs database of the Czech Republic under the tax information system. In the SR, there is no similar system for the transmission of information on imports and exports of goods between customs and tax administrations.</seg>
<seg id="260">The procedure for verifying the performance of the VAT administration and SpD was not the same, given the different legislation and conditions in the territory of the two States.</seg>
<seg id="261">The SAO verified the necessary data from information obtained with the Czech Customs Administration and from documents available at audited tax offices. The SAO of the Slovak Republic verified the execution of commercial transactions from documents of tax entities requested through the tax authorities.</seg>
<seg id="262">If irregularities were found, he asked the tax authorities to carry out tax checks.</seg>
<seg id="263">Parallel VAT and SpD controls carried out assessed the state of administration of these taxes in the run-up to accession to the European Union and pointed to the need for further cooperation in this area.</seg>
<seg id="264">Mutual cooperation will be further enhanced in monitoring the activities of financial and tax authorities in the context of the adoption of the new VAT law.</seg>
<seg id="265">One of the new obligations related to the delivery of goods to other Member States of the European Union is the submission of a so-called recapitulative statement.</seg>
<seg id="266">This report must be made by all VAT payers who have made a supply of goods to another Member State to a person registered for VAT in another Member State.</seg>
<seg id="267">Tax administrators are required to enter the data from the recapitulative statements into the VIES (VAT Information Exchange System) system, to which tax administrators from the Member States of the European Union have access.</seg>
<seg id="268">The financial or tax authorities then have the possibility to compare this data with the data contained in the submitted VAT returns.</seg>
<seg id="269">This system is further used to verify the validity of VAT registration number of persons, verify the validity of the VAT exemption applied on the supply of goods to another Member State and check the proper taxation of the goods.</seg>
<seg id="270">The implementation of parallel control actions showed the possibilities of cooperation between the SAO and the SAO of the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="271">The results of these control actions will confront the outputs of the control actions being prepared, which will inter alia focus on examining the VIES system to prevent tax evasion in so-called 'intra-Community supplies'.</seg>
<seg id="272">Given the importance of VAT and SpD for budgetary revenue, the need to focus control activities primarily on monitoring and identifying risk areas in order to reduce the scope for tax evasion on indirect taxes.</seg>
<seg id="273">Communiqué</seg>
<seg id="274">This report was prepared in Czech, English and Slovak languages and signed by the Vice-President of the Supreme Audit Office and the President of the Najvyššie Audit Office of the Slovak Republic.</seg>
</p>
