<doc docid="testsuite-segment_65-KA_04_23" genre="news" origlang="cs" sysid="CUNI-Transformer2018">
<p>
<seg id="1">Report on results of asylum checks in the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic</seg>
<seg id="2">State assets and funds intended to safeguard the activities of the Ministry of the Interior's Refugee Facilities Administration</seg>
<seg id="3">Control action No 04/23 "State property and funds intended to safeguard the activities of the Ministry of the Interior's Administration of Refugee Facilities"</seg>
<seg id="4">Control action No 15/2004 ‘Control of hospodárenia with staff assets and funds intended to provide asylum and temporary sanctuary cudzincom in SR’</seg>
<seg id="5">1. Introduction</seg>
<seg id="6">The migration of the population is one of the phenomena that are global in nature and have become an integral part of the current development phase of the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="7">It is mainly due to the flight of citizens from their country of origin or last place of residence from persecution, in particular for reasons of race, religion, nationality, politics, as well as the consequences of military conflicts and ethnic cleansing.</seg>
<seg id="8">Their aim is to gain asylum and integration into society, especially in some of the advanced democratic countries of Europe.</seg>
<seg id="9">Foreigners are also a large group, driven by unfavourable economic and living conditions.</seg>
<seg id="10">Migration is not a new phenomenon.</seg>
<seg id="11">The adoption of the 1951 Geneva Agreement and the 1967 New York Protocol on the Status of Refugees, both of which the governments of the signatory countries have pledged to apply in their foreign-policy orientations, has already established specific principles for helping refugees.</seg>
<seg id="12">The Czech and Slovak Federative Republic ratified the New York Protocol in 1991 and the Geneva Agreement in 1992.</seg>
<seg id="13">Both the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic declared their position on the refugee issue after the split in 1993 by continuing to implement adopted international documents, and their binding nature under national legislation was confirmed by a legal act.</seg>
<seg id="14">Both republics have also enshrined the granting of asylum in their constitutional laws.</seg>
<seg id="15">Parallel checks carried out by the Supreme Audit Office, the Czech Republic and the NajHigher Audit Office of the Slovak Republic were focused on the asylum process and related issues, the results of which are included in the joint final report.</seg>
<seg id="16">Cooperation between the supreme audit institutions of the two countries was carried out on the basis of the "Control Cooperation Treaty" (the "Treaty") concluded in April 2004.</seg>
<seg id="17">The two Parties have undertaken in the Treaty to provide each other with information on the legislation governing asylum procedures in the State of the other Party, selected statistics on the number of asylum seekers and the results of the asylum process, as well as information on asylum facilities.</seg>
<seg id="18">The aim of the parallel control action was to identify the same problem areas and to highlight the consequences of this for the area of population migration.</seg>
<seg id="19">Cooperation consisted in the unification of the programme of control actions, the exchange of information within the scope set out in the Treaty and the drawing up of a joint final report on the outcome of controls.</seg>
<seg id="20">The first joint meeting, which took place from 5.4 to 7.4.2004, set out identical sets of controlled issues and control procedures in the preparation of control actions.</seg>
<seg id="21">At the second meeting, which took place from 28.6 to 30.6.2004, the common points for the control action programme were specified.</seg>
<seg id="22">During the third joint meeting, which took place during the audit event from 8.11 to 10.11.2004, there was an exchange of experience on ongoing inspections.</seg>
<seg id="23">The modalities of the outputs from the controls have been specified and the structure and content of the joint final report, which was drawn up on 14.2 to 17.2.2005 at the last joint meeting, has been provisionally determined.</seg>
<seg id="24">The checks were carried out in parallel between September 2004 and January 2005.</seg>
<seg id="25">In the Czech Republic, inspectors of the Defence and Security Department and selected territorial unions carried out the inspection.</seg>
<seg id="26">The audited persons were the Ministry of the Interior (MV) and the Administration of Refugee Facilities of the Ministry of the Interior (SUZ).</seg>
<seg id="27">In the Slovak Republic, the section of defence, vnútra and štátnych úradov was inspected.</seg>
<seg id="28">The audited entity was the Migračný úrad Ministerstva vnútra SR (Ministry of Interior).</seg>
<seg id="29">The audited period was 2001, 2002, 2003 (the audited period).</seg>
<seg id="30">In some cases, statistics for a longer period of time are also used in the joint report.</seg>
<seg id="31">2. Review of control results</seg>
<seg id="32">2.1. Assessment of control activities</seg>
<seg id="33">The subject of the checks carried out in parallel were: - the asylum process, - the asylum facilities, - the management of the State's funds and assets, - the internal control system.</seg>
<seg id="34">The mutual exchange of lessons learned between the Supreme Audit Office, the Czech Republic and the NajHigher Audit Office of the Slovak Republic took place at the stage of preparation and implementation of control actions.</seg>
<seg id="35">This exchange allowed for a more thorough evaluation of the submissions, an analysis of the causes of the identified differences in the safeguarding of the asylum process.</seg>
<seg id="36">This made it possible to focus on the critical issues affecting the operation of asylum facilities.</seg>
<seg id="37">Ultimately, this had a positive effect on the quality of the control work carried out.</seg>
<seg id="38">2.2 Summary of control results</seg>
<seg id="39">The harmonisation of the asylum law of the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic with European Union (EU) documents has been the subject of European Commission evaluation reports on the readiness of both countries to join the EU.</seg>
<seg id="40">Legislation in this area continues after the accession of both countries to the EU with a view to further harmonisation with EU law.</seg>
<seg id="41">The number of asylum seekers in the Czech Republic increased significantly in 2001.</seg>
<seg id="42">In the Slovak Republic, the number of applicants is on a steadily growing trend, with a significant increase in applicants occurring in 2001.</seg>
<seg id="43">The Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic, within the meaning of international agreements, provide financial and material security to asylum seekers.</seg>
<seg id="44">Both countries' national budgets allocate the necessary funds for this purpose.</seg>
<seg id="45">The amount of expenditure drawn from the national budget of the two countries is influenced in particular by the number of applicants, the duration of the asylum procedure until the granting or non-granting of asylum, as well as the state of health of the applicants.</seg>
<seg id="46">The amount of some benefits collected is comparable in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="47">The Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic established asylum facilities in which they gradually created suitable conditions for the stay of participants in asylum procedures.</seg>
<seg id="48">Asylum facilities provide asylum seekers with accommodation, meals, health care and basic material equipment and hygiene supplies during their stay.</seg>
<seg id="49">At the same time, courses are organised in leisure activities and the applicants are created the conditions for cultural and sporting enjoyment.</seg>
<seg id="50">Asylum facilities include reception centres and residential centres, as well as integration centres in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="51">The cost per stay day depends on the occupancy and amenities of the centre and is comparable in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="52">In the Czech Republic, the capacity of asylum facilities is basically stabilised.</seg>
<seg id="53">In the Slovak Republic, it is projected to increase by almost 1,000 seats in the next two years.</seg>
<seg id="54">The aim is to create the conditions for applicants, an increasing number of whom are expected to continue to apply the Dublin Convention in the coming years.</seg>
<seg id="55">In the Czech Republic, the highest part of the approved budget expenditure was spent on service security. The crucial expenditure under this heading was expenditure on accommodation and catering for applicants in asylum facilities operated under contract, expenditure on healthcare provided to asylum seekers and the cost of a permanent security service for the protection of asylum facilities.</seg>
<seg id="56">Expenditure on salaries, payments for work carried out and insurance premiums also accounted for a significant proportion of total expenditure.</seg>
<seg id="57">In the Slovak Republic, the budgetary management of the security of migration policy and the asylum process was marked by many budget measures addressing legitimate demands related to the increase in the number of asylum seekers.</seg>
<seg id="58">Expenditure on wages, salaries and insurance premiums, expenditure on materials and services, and expenditure on security services have all contributed decisively to current spending.</seg>
<seg id="59">The results of the audit in the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic highlighted some similar deficiencies which did not have a major impact on the financial and asset management of the State.</seg>
<seg id="60">These were particularly shortcomings in the use of State budget funds, contrary to the purpose for which they were determined by the Finance Act, when current expenditure covered actions having the character of a technical valuation of fixed tangible assets.</seg>
<seg id="61">The Accounting Act on Inventories and on Non-Compliance with the Chart of Accounts was also breached.</seg>
<seg id="62">In the Czech Republic, minor deficiencies were also found in the disposal of the state's property when it was left to be used by another person without a contract.</seg>
<seg id="63">Failure to comply with the deadline for reporting changes to the Land Registry data breached the Land Registry Act and breached the Waste Act by leaving the waste for disposal to a person who was not the person authorised to handle the waste.</seg>
<seg id="64">In addition, deficiencies were found in the Slovak Republic in the provision of unduly large advances for electricity and natural gas collection, deficiencies in public procurement and in the management of the state's assets when its record was not sufficiently secured and the method of disposing of unnecessary assets was not demonstrated.</seg>
<seg id="65">The internal control system has been ensured in the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic within the meaning of the general binding legislation in force governing the way financial control is carried out.</seg>
<seg id="66">There were no deficiencies in the written documentation submitted.</seg>
<seg id="67">Despite some shortcomings identified, the Supreme Audit Office, the Czech Republic and the Najvyšší Audit Office of the Slovak Republic are positive about the process of SUZ and the Ministry in securing services for asylum seekers.</seg>
<seg id="68">Building on the lessons learned during the inspection, the Supreme Audit Office, the Czech Republic and the Najvyšší kontrolný úrad Slovenskej republiky note that, despite the significant increase in the number of asylum seekers in recent years, the respective organisational units of both countries have managed the tasks related to the care of asylum seekers at an appropriate level.</seg>
<seg id="69">The evaluation shows that the system is functional and stable.</seg>
<seg id="70">The results of the inspection were discussed with interested statutory representatives of the relevant organisational units of the state on both the Czech and Slovak sides.</seg>
<seg id="71">Based on the results of the inspection, we recommend that the positive methodological experience of the inspection is used in other joint control actions within the international cooperation of supreme audit institutions.</seg>
<seg id="72">3. Legislative framework</seg>
<seg id="73">In both the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic, asylum law is based on the 1951 Geneva Convention (the Convention relating to the Status of Refugees and the subsequent New York Protocol of 1967).</seg>
<seg id="74">The first legislation was implemented by Act No 498/1990 Coll., on refugees.</seg>
<seg id="75">In the Czech Republic, Act No 325/1999 Coll., on Asylum and Amending Act No 83/1991 Coll., on the Police of the Czech Republic, has been effective since 1 January 2000.</seg>
<seg id="76">This Act has been amended a total of five times (Act No 2/2002 Coll., Act No 217/2002 Coll., Act No 320/2002 Coll., Act No 519/2002 Coll. and Act No 222/2003 Coll.).</seg>
<seg id="77">There are currently two other amendments to Act No 325/1999 on Asylum in the legislative process, and the adoption of further amendments will be linked to European legislation.</seg>
<seg id="78">At the time of law 325/1999 on asylum, the area of asylum was part of the 3rd pillar of the EU and documents on asylum were political documents in their binding nature.</seg>
<seg id="79">Already, as part of the adoption of this law, there was an effort to make it as compatible as possible with EU law.</seg>
<seg id="80">A major change for asylum policy within the EU was the transfer of asylum issues from the 3rd to 1st pillar, when asylum law became part of Community law from 1.5.1999 under the Treaty of Amsterdam.</seg>
<seg id="81">This shift has created the need to create appropriate legislation as well, i.e. to create legal instruments in an appropriate binding legal order.</seg>
<seg id="82">The compatibility of Czech asylum law with EU documents has been the subject of regular evaluation reports by the European Commission.</seg>
<seg id="83">Key Community Asylum Regulations were adopted shortly before or after the Czech Republic's accession to the EU and their transposition period at the time of the Supreme Audit Office's inspection, the Czech Republic has not yet expired.</seg>
<seg id="84">Once implemented in the Czech legal order, the Czech Republic will be obliged to notify the European Commission of how it has implemented the transposition.</seg>
<seg id="85">In the Slovak Republic, the procedure of state authorities in the procedure for granting refugee status and determining the obligations of foreigners who have applied for refugee status, or who have been granted temporary refuge in the territory of the Slovak Republic, was laid down, with effect from 1 January 1996, by the National Council of the Slovak Republic Act No 283/1995 Z. z., on utechencoch.</seg>
<seg id="86">Since 2003, the Refugee Act has been replaced by Act No 480/2002 Z. z ‘ on asylum and amending and supplementing certain laws, incorporating the harmonisation of the legislation of the Slovak Republic with Council of Europe Directive 2001/55/EC of 20.7.2001 on minimum standards for providing temporary protection in the event of a mass influx of displaced persons and on measures to promote the balance of efforts between Member States in receiving such persons and bearing the resulting consequences.</seg>
<seg id="87">Following two amendments to Act No 480/2002 Z z., on asylum, in 2003 and 2004, a third amendment was approved at the beginning of 2005, which means further harmonisation of the law of the Slovak Republic with EU legislation on migration and asylum.</seg>
<seg id="88">Its important elements include, for example, making it compulsory for asylum seekers to attend a Slovak language foundation course during their stay at the integration centre, appointing a guardian to the courts for non-legal aliens if they are staying in the territory of the Slovak Republic without a legal representative, allowing applicants to enter into an employment relationship in certain circumstances, as set out in an amendment to the law.</seg>
