<seg id="2">Introduction Word</seg>
<seg id="3">Without trans-European transport networks, a modern, dynamic and, above all, united Europe would be hard to imagine.</seg>
<seg id="4">Quality transport networks are a prerequisite for maintaining and raising the standard of living of Europeans.</seg>
<seg id="5">Creating the conditions for fast, safe, reliable and cheap transport of people and costs is an important task for government.</seg>
<seg id="6">This is a very demanding task, both organisational and technical and financial.</seg>
<seg id="7">Europe's efforts at sustainable mobility are often and hard to compromise with Europe's interest in maintaining a healthy and human-friendly environment.</seg>
<seg id="8">Constructions of transport infrastructure, even with the necessary environmental measures, are financially challenging.</seg>
<seg id="9">Considerable government procedures and decisions in the preparation and acquisition of transport structures can bring significant savings in public financial resources that can be used in other ways for the benefit of citizens.</seg>
<seg id="10">One of the roles of the audit institutions is to actively seek deficiencies that have led to lower than achievable economy, efficiency and effectiveness of spending on transport infrastructure construction.</seg>
<seg id="11">The audit institutions should not only draw the attention of the state administration to the shortcomings identified, but recommend measures to improve the situation, for the benefit of citizens, for the benefit of Europe.</seg>
<seg id="12">Short Summary</seg>
<seg id="13">In 2005 and 2006, the two supreme audit institutions of the Federal Republic of Germany and the Czech Republic (hereinafter referred to as the Federal Republic of Germany and the Czech Republic) Bundesrechnungshof (hereinafter referred to as BRH) and the Supreme Audit Office (hereinafter referred to as the SAO) carried out parallel checks on expenditure on the construction of the Prague-Dresden motorway (the D 8 motorway in the Czech Republic and the A 17 motorway in the Federal Republic of Germany).</seg>
<seg id="14">The highways are connected by a border bridge that is co-financed by both countries.</seg>
<seg id="15">Thanks to cooperation with the SAO, BRH was able to carry out a thorough check of the effectiveness of the funds spent on the construction of the border bridge.</seg>
<seg id="16">Based on close cooperation with BRH, the SAO obtained the necessary data on the level of German costs for bridges and tunnels for comparative purposes.</seg>
<seg id="17">The Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany concluded a contract in 2000 for the construction of a border bridge.</seg>
<seg id="18">Eventually, according to the construction process, the completion date was scheduled for the end of 2006.</seg>
<seg id="19">However, during the award procedure, the Directorate of Roads and Highways of the Czech Republic (hereinafter referred to as the RMD) made errors which led to an extension of the competition period and a reduction of the construction time.</seg>
<seg id="20">The contract with the contractor was thus signed later than anticipated.</seg>
<seg id="21">The contractor agreed to build the bridge in a shorter time and ensure its completion in 2006.</seg>
<seg id="22">As a result, however, the RMD had to accept a significant increase in the price of the bridge.</seg>
<seg id="23">As part of the joint inspection work, bridge prices on the D 8 and A 17 motorways were compared on a per square metre basis for the bridge structure.</seg>
<seg id="24">Statistical analysis of prices made it possible to identify bridges with high costs per square metre.</seg>
<seg id="25">Analysis revealed that the border bridge was the most expensive bridge in a group of large bridges with a length of over 100 metres.</seg>
<seg id="26">The price increase could also be attributed to delays in the procurement process.</seg>
<seg id="27">When analysing the cost of building the tunnels, the inspectors found that tunnel prices on the D 8 motorway were significantly higher than those of comparable tunnels in the SRN.</seg>
<seg id="28">BRH and the SAO now have a database on the prices of bridges and tunnels, which they will be able to rely on for future checks on the efficiency of the funds used for transport infrastructure purposes.</seg>
<seg id="29">For the construction of bridges, both monitoring institutions recommend: standardisation of bridge structures and the use of coupled steel-concrete and special structures only when pre-stressed reinforced concrete bridges are not adequate.</seg>
<seg id="30">Her team spirit and informality were among the main signs of cooperation.</seg>
<seg id="31">During the parallel inspection, the controllers shared their specific knowledge and skills.</seg>
<seg id="32">Introduction</seg>
<seg id="33">This report reports on the progress and results of the parallel checks of funds spent on the construction of the motorway linking Dresden and Prague (D 8 in the Czech Republic and A 17 in Germany).</seg>
<seg id="34">The controls were focused on the economy, efficiency and effectiveness of the expenditure incurred.</seg>
<seg id="35">Parallel inspections were carried out by BRH in Germany and the SAO in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="36">Parallel controls took place in 2005 and 2006.</seg>
<seg id="37">The SAO audited the economy, efficiency and effectiveness of expenditure of approximately CZK 20 billion including VAT (approximately €690 million) on the frontier section of the D 8 motorway, which is numbered 0807.</seg>
<seg id="38">Of this amount, €64 million of European funds (ISPA) was planned to be used.</seg>
<seg id="39">In addition to the parallel inspection carried out with the SAO, BRH audited the preparation and construction of the A 17 motorway in 2003 and 2005.</seg>
<seg id="40">The funds spent on the construction of all three sections of the A 17 motorway amounted to some €670 million, of which €277 million will be co-financed by European funds (EFRE).</seg>
<seg id="41">The motorway from Prague to Dresden is part of the Trans-European Transport Corridor IV. Dresden - central and southern parts of Eastern Europe - Istanbul.</seg>
<seg id="42">Highway D 8 runs from Prague through Ústí nad Labem to the state border.</seg>
<seg id="43">Highway A-17 runs from the Czech Republic/Germany border to Dresden.</seg>
<seg id="44">Border sections of both motorways were under construction at the time of the inspection.</seg>
<seg id="45">These sections became operational on 21 December 2006.</seg>
<seg id="46">On the German side, the motorway is thus completed as far as Dresden, while on the Czech side of highway D 8 it is not completed, as section 0805, covering 16.4 km through the Czech Central Mountains between Řehlovice and Lovosicemi, is still in the preparation phase.</seg>
<seg id="47">According to the plan, section 0805 between Prague and Ústí nad Labem is to pass through the protected landscape area of České středohoří.</seg>
<seg id="48">According to forecasts made in the Czech Republic in 2001, there should be 22,940 vehicles per day on the cross-border section 0807 of the D 8 motorway in 2008.</seg>
<seg id="49">According to German forecasts, the traffic intensity at the Czech border will total about 25,000 vehicles per day in 2010.</seg>
<seg id="50">In 2000, Germany and the Czech Republic concluded the Treaty between the Federal Republic of Germany and the Czech Republic to link the German motorway A 17 and the Czech motorway D 8 to the common national border by building a border bridge.</seg>
<seg id="51">Both States are involved in the construction of the bridge, therefore the control of the construction of this bridge was an important aspect of the parallel controls carried out by the two control institutions.</seg>
<seg id="52">Cooperation of BRH and SAO</seg>
<seg id="53">Since mid-2005, the two supreme audit institutions have discussed working closely together to control the construction of the motorway linking Prague and Dresden.</seg>
<seg id="54">Both sides had serious reasons for such cooperation:</seg>
<seg id="55">1.</seg>
<seg id="56">The SRN is financially involved in the construction of the border bridge.</seg>
<seg id="57">Its planning and construction rests with the RMD.</seg>
<seg id="58">Therefore, BRH itself did not have the opportunity to inspect this construction project.</seg>
<seg id="59">2.</seg>
<seg id="60">The SAO did not have the comparative database needed to assess whether the funds had been used cost-effectively in relation to the overall level of costs for bridges and tunnels at D 8.</seg>
<seg id="61">3.</seg>
<seg id="62">The SAO needed to ascertain the effectiveness of the expenditure, taking into account the main technical parameters of the motorway, in particular the arrangement of bridges and tunnels, which should allow the same quality of driving on both sides of the border.</seg>
<seg id="63">Following preparatory negotiations, the agreement on coordinated control of the D 8/A 17 motorway was signed by the presidents of the two supreme audit institutions on 4 January 2006.</seg>
<seg id="64">The joint working meetings of the BRH auditors and the SAO took place over the whole of 2006 at an interval of approximately six to eight weeks.</seg>
<seg id="65">The meetings addressed current issues and challenges, in particular the preparation of a uniform methodology for controlling the prices of bridges and tunnels, the exchange of findings from the inspection of the construction of the border bridge and the preparation of joint reports.</seg>
<seg id="66">The continuous exchange of information was a major sign of cooperation.</seg>
<seg id="67">While BRH did most of the work on comparing the technical parameters of bridges and tunnels and tendering procedures, the SAO largely prepared a methodology for controlling the prices of bridges and tunnels.</seg>
<seg id="68">The applicable legal standards for government control differ in the way control actions are closed in the two countries.</seg>
<seg id="69">For these reasons, the two supreme audit institutions drew their own control conclusions on their findings, obtained during their inspections.</seg>
<seg id="70">This report reflects the results achieved through parallel controls.</seg>
<seg id="71">The cooperation will end with the signing of the final communiqué in the first half of 2007.</seg>
<seg id="72">Border bridge construction</seg>
<seg id="73">The Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany agreed in a 2000 contract on the completion date of the construction of the border bridge, as far as possible, in 2005.</seg>
<seg id="74">The two sides then agreed to postpone this date until the end of 2006.</seg>
<seg id="75">The RMD acted as investor.</seg>
<seg id="76">The SRN is financially involved in building the bridge out of 42.13%.</seg>
<seg id="77">In the period up to 1999, the RMD proposed that the border bridge should have a pre-stressed reinforced concrete structure.</seg>
<seg id="78">In 1999, in agreement with its partners in Germany, the RMD agreed to a bonded steel-concrete structure.</seg>
<seg id="79">This decision was justified by the reduction of the number of twin pillars from seven to five and the subsequent environmental benefits of such a solution for the valley.</seg>
<seg id="80">In addition, comparative calculations carried out by the RMD indicated that the braced steel-concrete structure should be a less expensive option.</seg>
<seg id="81">But there was a mistake in the calculations.</seg>
<seg id="82">They stated that the new fused steel-concrete structure would be only 397m long.</seg>
<seg id="83">In fact, it's 5% longer.</seg>
<seg id="84">During the award of the contract for the border bridge, the RMD made serious errors.</seg>
<seg id="85">It has not prepared contract documentation that adequately describes the assessment criteria and sub-criteria for the comparison of tenders.</seg>
<seg id="86">This error resulted in the bid evaluation and evaluation panel and the Director-General evaluating the bids in a subjective and problematic manner.</seg>
<seg id="87">The unsuccessful tenderer contested the results of the contract procedure.</seg>
<seg id="88">Subsequent investigations by the Competition Authority led to the contract for the construction contract being signed later than initially calculated.</seg>
<seg id="89">This meant that the 2004 summer construction season, following the evaluation of the bids, was wasted and the time allocated to construction was reduced.</seg>
<seg id="90">The construction company agreed to build the bridge in less time, but at a substantial cost increase.</seg>
<seg id="91">The process offered included the double installation of a bridge top, a change in the structure of the pillars and the establishment and fitting-out of mounting spaces.</seg>
<seg id="92">In addition, the construction company was unable to procure the type of steel originally proposed by the required deadline.</seg>
<seg id="93">The new type of steel – at a cost of some €4 million more, which had to be paid in full by the RMD – allowed a reduction in the time taken to implement anti-corrosion protection, which in turn enabled the overall construction time of the border bridge to be reduced.</seg>
<seg id="94">Compared to the net price of €18.3 million offered in the tender, the total cost of building the border bridge will increase considerably as a result of the accelerated procedure and other adjustments in financing.</seg>
<seg id="95">The reduced time allocated to construction work led to a price increase of about €5.9 million.</seg>
<seg id="96">At present, the net cost amount is around €25.9 million, not taking into account automatic price increases (as of October 2006).</seg>
<seg id="97">Comparison of bridge and tunnel prices</seg>
<seg id="98">The two supreme audit institutions carried out an analysis of the prices of bridges on the D 8 and A 17 motorways in order to identify bridges that were priced too high and to compare the prices of bridges on the German and Czech sides.</seg>
<seg id="99">The analysis relied on methods of mathematical statistics.</seg>
<seg id="100">Furthermore, tunnels on D 8 were compared with similar tunnels on the SRN motorways (A 71, A 38 and A 4).</seg>
<seg id="101">There are no similar tunnels on the A 17.</seg>
<seg id="102">In preparing this part of the inspection, it was important to accurately identify the relevant prices.</seg>
<seg id="103">The two supreme audit institutions have established the following principles for comparing bridge prices: based on the actual price paid for the bridge, excluding value added tax (VAT rates vary and are subject to change in the Czech Republic and SNR); do not take into account prices for the special foundations of the bridge; convert prices in CZK into € at the European Central Bank rate applicable on 30.12.2005 (CZK 29 = € 1).</seg>
<seg id="104">Both D 8 and A 17 have bridges of different designs (steel-concrete, pre-stressed reinforced concrete, joined-together steel-concrete and steel) and different sizes.</seg>
<seg id="105">In order to ensure the homogeneity of the structures examined, the bridges were divided into groups according to the type of construction.</seg>
<seg id="106">Within these groups, the size of the bridge was also taken into account in the analyses.</seg>
<seg id="107">By far the most common type of construction was concrete bridges on both sides of the boundary (20 bridges on D 8, 36 bridges on A 17).</seg>
<seg id="108">The analysis concentrated mainly on this group of bridges, as the size of the population allowed the use of mathematical-statistical methods with a high degree of reliability of results.</seg>
<seg id="109">Checks found that prices per m 2 of concrete bridges on both D 8 and A 17 depend on the size of the bridge (length, area): the larger the bridge, the lower the price per m2 of bridge construction.</seg>
<seg id="110">For German bridges, the price's dependence on size was stronger than for Czech bridges (see charts below).</seg>
<seg id="111">Two concrete bridges at A 17 and four at D 8 have been identified and are priced significantly higher.</seg>
<seg id="112">A method to detect atypical values in a set of numbers was used to locate these bridges, as well as a regression analysis taking into account the bridge price's dependence on its size (for determining atypically expensive bridges, the standard distance from the regression curve is upwards).</seg>
<seg id="113">However, information about the atypically high price of those bridges should only be seen as an indication of which bridges need to be targeted.</seg>
<seg id="114">In order to draw a generally applicable conclusion, the causes of the high price in each case identified should be analysed.</seg>
<seg id="115">One such cause may be inefficient administrative action, or environmental requirements or some other plausible reason.</seg>
<seg id="116">Given that Czech concrete bridges are on average longer than German ones (see table below), the proven negative dependence of the bridge price on its length could lead to the assumption that Czech bridges should be cheaper.</seg>
<seg id="117">The hypothesis of lower prices for Czech concrete bridges is also supported by lower labour costs in the Czech construction sector compared to the SRN.</seg>
<seg id="118">On the contrary, the results of the analysis show that the prices of concrete bridges at D 8 are higher than at A 17.</seg>
<seg id="119">Two possible causes for this have been identified during the joint negotiations:</seg>
<seg id="120">1.</seg>
<seg id="121">In Germany, most bridges are awarded as separate contracts.</seg>
<seg id="122">Such an award allows small and medium-sized regional firms to take part in the tender.</seg>
<seg id="123">In the Czech Republic, many bridges are awarded as part of a contract for part of the motorway route, which is several kilometres long.</seg>
<seg id="124">Small and medium-sized companies do not participate in such a competition because the contract is too big for them.</seg>
<seg id="125">2.</seg>
<seg id="126">There is more variability in bridge designs in the CR than in the SRN.</seg>
<seg id="127">In this context, the SAO found that the type of bridge construction is decided long before its construction.</seg>
<seg id="128">The decision is taken at the time when the RMD submits an application for a territorial decision.</seg>
<seg id="129">Although the RMD selects bridge types from several variants at this time, economy plays a minor role in decision-making.</seg>
<seg id="130">A general conclusion on the prices of bridges in the Czech Republic and Germany could only be reached on the basis of a thorough analysis of the construction works market in both countries, which would, however, go beyond this control action.</seg>
<seg id="131">The border bridge is the most expensive coupled ocelobeton bridge at D 8 and A 17.</seg>
<seg id="132">In the case of tunnels, it was found that tunnel prices on the D 8 are twice as high as tunnels in the SRN.</seg>
<seg id="133">However, a comparison of the main construction-technical parameters of the tunnels on the D 8 with the tunnels in the SRN showed no significant difference.</seg>
<seg id="134">Significant price differences could be attributed to the fact that there is no real competition in the tunnel construction industry in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="135">However, the small number of tunnels did not allow general conclusions to be drawn.</seg>
<seg id="136">Effectiveness and efficiency of the construction of the Dresden-Prague motorway</seg>
<seg id="137">A separate CR was created in 1993.</seg>
<seg id="138">In the same year, the government approved the concept of development of the motorway network.</seg>
<seg id="139">The D 8 motorway was to be gradually extended from Prague to the national border with Germany.</seg>
<seg id="140">Section No 0805 through the Czech Central Mountains was to be acquired before the border section No 0807.</seg>
<seg id="141">The Czech Republic acquires the D 8 motorway under programme financing.</seg>
<seg id="142">In programme No 327 220 ‘Construction of the D 8 motorway Prague – Ústí nad Labem – state border of the Czech Republic/SRN” set two objectives for the construction of the D 8 motorway:</seg>
<seg id="143">1.</seg>
<seg id="144">improve the connection between Prague and Ústí nad Labem – a national objective;</seg>
<seg id="145">2.</seg>
<seg id="146">improve the connection between Prague and Berlin within the framework of the IV Trans-European Transport Corridor Berlin-Istanbul - an international objective.</seg>
<seg id="147">According to the programme, the construction of the section leading through the Czech Central Mountains was to be completed in June 2008 and the construction of the border section No 0807 in June 2007.</seg>
<seg id="148">It should be added here that the completion date is not identical to the commissioning date.</seg>
<seg id="149">The SAO found that the preparation of the construction of the section leading through the Czech Central Mountains is now at the stage of an official territorial decision.</seg>
<seg id="150">Environmental activists have challenged the decision with lawsuits.</seg>
<seg id="151">There is no final decision on the claims.</seg>
<seg id="152">It can therefore not be excluded that the section running through the Czech Central Mountains will be completed several years later than indicated in the documentation of the programme.</seg>
<seg id="153">In the summer of 2006, the Czech Ministry of Transport proposed to postpone the date of completion of section 0805 until 2010.</seg>
<seg id="154">As a result of these facts, the construction of the cross-border section has not achieved the national objective of improving the link between Prague and Ústí nad Labem.</seg>
<seg id="155">The RMD made an estimate of capital expenditure for the border section D 8 No 0807 and section No 0805 through the Czech Central Mountains in 1999-2001.</seg>
<seg id="156">The estimate in these capital expenditure included investment costs is about €639 million combined for both Sections Nos 0805 and 0807.</seg>
<seg id="157">Table 2: Economic Assessment Results (EIRR = Internal Rate of Yield)</seg>
<seg id="158">All motorways and expressways under consideration open, both sections of D 8 opened in 2007.</seg>
<seg id="159">On the northern part of the border section, the traffic intensity of 18,000 vehicles a day in 2010</seg>
<seg id="160">All motorways and expressways under consideration open, both sections of D 8 opened in 2007.</seg>
<seg id="161">On the northern part of the border section, the traffic intensity of 22,000 vehicles a day in 2010</seg>
<seg id="162">All motorways and expressways under consideration open, both sections of D 8 opened in 2007.</seg>
<seg id="163">On the northern part of the border section, the traffic intensity of 25,000 vehicles a day in 2010</seg>
<seg id="164">An economic analysis carried out in 2001 was based on the assumption that the border section and the section through the Czech Central Mountains would be completed in time.</seg>
<seg id="165">However, at the time of the inspection, it is clear that the section through the Czech Central Mountains will not be opened at the original date.</seg>
<seg id="166">This will reduce the aforementioned EIRRs.</seg>
<seg id="167">The cost of both sections, net of VAT, as at 31.12.2005, was €897 million, i.e. higher by 27.4% than the cost level used in the economic analysis in 2001.</seg>
<seg id="168">However, there is a risk that section 0805 will be run on a different, more expensive route, which would affect the aforementioned threshold of economic viability.</seg>
<seg id="169">Economic analysis has shown that the construction of both sections of the motorway is economically viable at a traffic intensity of at least 18,000 vehicles per day in 2010.</seg>
<seg id="170">The forecast for 2008 was 22,940 vehicles, but a study addressing the issue of bypass routes for the missing section across the Czech Central Highlands calculates a traffic intensity of 12,600 to 13,750 vehicles per day, pushing the investment below the threshold of economic viability.</seg>
<seg id="171">With the higher load of commuter routes for the missing section through the Czech Central Mountains, there is a high probability of congestion and thus an increase in external costs, which was not foreseen in the original economic analysis.</seg>
<seg id="172">The above mentioned reduction in revenues and increase in costs means that the already low EIRR that the construction of the D 8 border section should have achieved will not be achieved.</seg>
<seg id="173">Construction of the D 8 border section is therefore inefficient.</seg>
<seg id="174">The construction of the A 17 motorway also involved similar cost overruns to those of the two sections on the D 8.</seg>
<seg id="175">As part of the overall economic assessment of the 1992 Federal Road Development Plan for Long-haul Transport, the Federal Ministry of Transport of Germany projected a cost of about €320 million.</seg>
<seg id="176">The resulting expense-income ratio was then 4.6.</seg>
<seg id="177">In the meantime, however, costs have risen sharply to about €670 million, and the cost-benefit ratio has more than halved.</seg>
<seg id="178">In addition to the parallel inspection carried out jointly with the SAO, BRH audited the preparation and construction of the A 17 motorway in 2003 and 2005.</seg>
<seg id="179">In doing so, BRH found that the relevant State Approval Authority had required an off-road tunnel for Section A 17, third section, which was not needed.</seg>
<seg id="180">In the course of the inspection, BRH managed to convince the Federal Ministry and the German road building administration that the tunnel was not necessary.</seg>
<seg id="181">This resulted in savings that amounted to around €10 million in construction costs alone and €0.15 million in annual operating costs.</seg>
<seg id="182">Assessing the first section of A 17, BRH found that the construction project had not been properly prepared.</seg>
<seg id="183">The following example illustrates this:</seg>
<seg id="184">At the preparatory stage, the Road Construction Authority did not investigate the conditions of the bedrock in the Dölzschen rocks because the site was difficult to access.</seg>
<seg id="185">This was done only after the tunnel stamping machine had struck the rock.</seg>
<seg id="186">Tests showed that the rocks were more weathered inside than anticipated during the selection process.</seg>
<seg id="187">Costly measures such as anchoring, injections and stone-falling protective nets, which cost about €3.3 million, therefore had to be taken.</seg>
<seg id="188">The Road and Motorway Directorate had to bear the costs not only of other extraordinary operations, such as safety measures in the rocks of Dölzschen, but also of measures that would not have been needed if the construction project had been properly prepared first.</seg>
<seg id="189">Expenditure of this kind includes costs related to the interruption of construction operations (€3.2 million), additional training for drilling staff (€0.5 million) and rising wages and expenditure on goods due to project overruns (€7 million).</seg>
<seg id="190">The cost overruns thus amounted to some €10.7 million, which was not matched by any value added.</seg>
<seg id="191">Based on the lessons learned from this and other audited projects, BRH asked the Federal Ministry to apply stricter guidance in its supervision of road construction works.</seg>
<seg id="192">In doing so, the Federal Ministry should give the Directorates of Roads and Highways the necessary incentive to introduce quality assurance systems.</seg>
<seg id="193">Benefits of cooperation for BRH and SAO Cooperation fulfilled the purpose of both audit institutions.</seg>
<seg id="194">BRH gained control knowledge of the preparation, assignment and progress of the construction of the border bridge.</seg>
<seg id="195">The two supreme audit institutions have built a database of bridge and tunnel prices on which future inspections can rely.</seg>
<seg id="196">The SAO found that the main construction-technical parameters of bridges, tunnels and route of the D 8 motorway do not differ from those of the A 17.</seg>
<seg id="197">The auditors of the two institutions involved in the cooperation have gained new experience, which they can use for further inspections.</seg>
</p>
