<p>
<seg id="1">Public works procurement and corruption prevention</seg>
<seg id="2">Joint report on parallel audit by Czech Supreme Audit Office (SAO) and German Federal Court of Auditors (BRH)</seg>
<seg id="3">Introduction and Overview</seg>
<seg id="4">Procurement of goods and services by contracting authorities is very important for both the state and private sectors.</seg>
<seg id="5">The role of the state is to use public resources as efficiently and cost-effectively as possible and to ensure fair and regulated free competition.</seg>
<seg id="6">In the European Union (EU), public procurement is a key factor for the success of the single economic area.</seg>
<seg id="7">In its regulations, the EU has set limits above which contracting authorities must meet certain requirements to guarantee a broad and unrestricted competitive environment across the EU.</seg>
<seg id="8">EU Member States must therefore transpose European procurement law into their national legislation and put it into practice.</seg>
<seg id="9">Both the Czech Republic and Germany have already done so.</seg>
<seg id="10">For public contracts below EU thresholds, the regulation of their award remains the responsibility of individual countries.</seg>
<seg id="11">Moreover, public procurement is vulnerable to corruption, with consequent high potential for harm.</seg>
<seg id="12">Therefore, contracting authorities are obliged to take reasonable measures in their procurement procedures to avoid corruption and unfair favouritism (prevention of corruption).</seg>
<seg id="13">In January 2011, the Supreme Audit Office of the Czech Republic (Czech SAI - NCA) and the Federal Court of Auditors of Germany (German SAI - BRH) agreed to conduct parallel checks in the field of procurement procedures and prevention of corruption in land and transport structures.</seg>
<seg id="14">Cooperation was also focused on the field of European procurement law as transposed into national legislation.</seg>
<seg id="15">Controls included awarding contracts below European limits in order to crack down on corruption prevention.</seg>
<seg id="16">The inspection findings of the two supreme audit institutions are summarised in a joint report addressed, inter alia, to international organisations such as the International Organisation of Supreme Audit Institutions (INTOSAI).</seg>
<seg id="17">Areas of control and audited institutions</seg>
<seg id="18">The BRH assessment is based on blanket inspections of the above-mentioned areas, which were carried out at the German construction administrations in charge of federal transport and land structures between 2011 and 2012.</seg>
<seg id="19">For example, motorway works and large-scale building projects were assessed.</seg>
<seg id="20">BRH included findings from past inspections in the evaluation.</seg>
<seg id="21">The SAO's assessment is based on inspections carried out during the years 2008 to 2012, which focused on construction of roads, railway lines, water projects, large buildings (hospitals, cultural facilities, universities) and some other buildings in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="22">In Germany, federal procurement is mostly carried out by the Land's building authorities.</seg>
<seg id="23">In the Czech Republic, the state institutions for road and rail construction are responsible for the procurement of transport infrastructure contracts.</seg>
<seg id="24">In the field of building, procurement is carried out by entities benefiting from budget funds.</seg>
<seg id="25">In both countries, the services of external experts are also used at each stage of the procurement process.</seg>
<seg id="26">The evaluation must take into account the differences in procurement legislation and the specificities of the construction market in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="27">Structure of public procurement law in both countries</seg>
<seg id="28">In Germany, the conduct of European procurement procedures is governed by laws and sub-statutory standards.</seg>
<seg id="29">Procurement procedures limited to Germany shall be governed by budgetary law and relevant administrative acts .</seg>
<seg id="30">The internal administrative rules contain numerous additional provisions for both European and national procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="31">Further details on the requirements of European procurement law and the prevention of corruption are set out in the federal government's so-called procurement manuals, in which the requirements are elaborated or formulated in greater detail, taking into account legal precedents in the field of procurement law.</seg>
<seg id="32">In the Czech Republic, public procurement is governed by the Public Procurement Act and other legislation concerning contracts with a value above and below European limits.</seg>
<seg id="33">The procurement law was substantially changed in 2012.</seg>
<seg id="34">The new rules have strengthened the transparency of procurement procedures, opened up scope for more competition and reduced opportunities for corruption during the procurement process.</seg>
<seg id="35">Essential aspects of procurement law in both countries</seg>
<seg id="36">As far as European procurement procedures are concerned, open and narrower procedures in particular need to be applied in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="37">In Germany, contracts below the European limit are awarded in accordance with national rules (public call for competition, restricted call for competition, negotiated procedures), but these are practically identical to the above-mentioned conditions for European procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="38">Public procurement in Germany is characterised by the principle of preference for open procedures (where candidates on a European scale are invited) and public calls for participation (only in the case of national procedures).</seg>
<seg id="39">In open procedures and when invited to take part in a contest, a tender may be submitted by any interested party.</seg>
<seg id="40">Another important feature of German procurement law is the support of small and medium-sized firms.</seg>
<seg id="41">This is achieved primarily by dividing the total procurement into business-specific lots and dividing into sub-contracts.</seg>
<seg id="42">The award of contracts divided into these lots gives as many candidates as possible a chance to participate in the procedure.</seg>
<seg id="43">The two characteristics of German procurement law are time-tested tools for getting good value for money.</seg>
<seg id="44">There are more than 330,000 construction companies registered in Germany with 1.9 million employees.</seg>
<seg id="45">In the Czech Republic, the terms of European procedures must be applied even in cases of public procurement with a value below the EU limit.</seg>
<seg id="46">The exception is the simplified sub-standard procedure, where the contracting authority can apply less onerous procedures.</seg>
<seg id="47">In accordance with European law, Czech procurement law includes the conditions under which the contract must be awarded in order to ensure competition and achieve a favourable price.</seg>
<seg id="48">Current Czech legislation allows contracting authorities to choose between an open procedure and a narrower procedure.</seg>
<seg id="49">There are 85,000 construction companies registered in the Czech Republic, of which about 1,900 have 20 or more employees.</seg>
<seg id="50">Total procurement volume of public works by contracting authorities and proportion of each type of procedure in both countries</seg>
<seg id="51">In 2011, the total volume of construction works in Germany amounted to EUR 7 675 billion.</seg>
<seg id="52">CZK 1,138 billion (15%) of which was the share of public contracts that included contracts awarded by individual Länder and municipalities, in addition to those awarded by the federal government.</seg>
<seg id="53">The total volume of federal road and land construction projects (excluding construction of railways and water structures) amounted to CZK 212.5 billion.</seg>
<seg id="54">In 2011, the composition of the federal land works and transport works contracts was as follows: 80,7 % open procedures and public calls; 12.7% narrower governance and challenges;</seg>
<seg id="55">6,6 % negotiated procedures and direct awards; 33.2% is the proportion of European procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="56">The volume of public construction contracts in the Czech Republic reached 118.6 billion CZK in 2011, which was about 25% of the total volume of all construction works.</seg>
<seg id="57">In 2009 it reached CZK 194.0 billion, which was 37% of the total.</seg>
<seg id="58">Structure of procurement types in 2011: 65.1% open procedures; 14,3 % restricted management; 9,5 % negotiated procedure; 8,4 % simplified procedures for sub-standard contracts; 2.7% other management.</seg>
<seg id="59">The figures include all supply, service and works contracts awarded by contracting authorities in 2011.</seg>
<seg id="60">These figures show that: parallel controls in both countries targeted a substantial proportion of public procurement procedures; prevention of corruption, which must be kept in mind in procurement procedures, has a significant financial impact; open significance. procurement procedures are of key importance.</seg>
<seg id="61">Summary of main results</seg>
<seg id="62">The SAO and BRH carried out parallel checks on the award of European works contracts, with an emphasis on preventing corruption in their countries.</seg>
<seg id="63">The inspections focused on comparing legislation in the two countries and the EU and on the implementation of land and transport procurement contracts.</seg>
<seg id="64">The following are the key findings:</seg>
<seg id="65">The EU Public Procurement Directive has been transposed into the national laws of both countries (points 1 and 3.1).</seg>
<seg id="66">Preventing corruption is not only the aim of the EU directive, but of the two countries' national procurement rules, which differ in part in both focus and detail.</seg>
<seg id="67">In both countries, the basic requirement that tender documents must meet is to include all the information needed to prepare tenders.</seg>
<seg id="68">The specification shall be neutral and shall not contain any requirements restricting competition.</seg>
<seg id="69">Tender documents in Germany generally meet these requirements.</seg>
<seg id="70">In the Czech Republic, the problem is the lack of definition of the subject matter of the contract.</seg>
<seg id="71">In Germany, splitting contracts into lots is required where possible in order to promote a competitive environment.</seg>
<seg id="72">According to BRH's findings, this requirement is respected in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="73">The SAO's inspections showed that in the Czech Republic considerable public works in the field of roadworks are commissioned without being divided into parts or being divided, but only into very significant parts in volume. This may distort competition and lead to restrictions on only a few large companies.</seg>
<seg id="74">These limitations on market potential can result in significant cost increases and create the risk of non-serious price negotiations and impermissible conventions.</seg>
<seg id="75">Legislation in both countries allows contracting authorities to award additional works under certain conditions if the need arises after the contract has been concluded (point 4.1).</seg>
<seg id="76">In both countries, the requirements for correctly determining the type of procurement procedure are met.</seg>
<seg id="77">In the Czech Republic, under the applicable regulations, contracting authorities are free to designate one of the open procurement procedures, namely an open procedure or a restricted procedure.</seg>
<seg id="78">German procurement and budgetary law enshrines the primacy of open procedures for both European tenures and national ones, known as public calls for competition.</seg>
<seg id="79">Open tender procedures in both countries allow a larger range of candidates to submit a bid and also reduce the risk of corruption by making it more difficult to collude illegally between bidders.</seg>
<seg id="80">At the same time, the best results in terms of value for money are being achieved.</seg>
<seg id="81">In the case of large contracts for which the estimated total price reaches or exceeds the limits set by the EU, the audited contracting authorities always launched a European procurement procedure.</seg>
<seg id="82">Correct determination of the estimated contract value plays a very important role in determining the type of procurement procedure.</seg>
<seg id="83">In Germany, databases are used to determine the price of public works objectively, in which values are based on completed construction projects.</seg>
<seg id="84">This is a sufficiently objective tool.</seg>
<seg id="85">In the Czech Republic, databases are used only in the area of road construction, but are not yet an effective tool (point 4.2).</seg>
<seg id="86">When awarding a works contract under European procurement procedures, prior information and contract notices need to be published in order to enhance competition by allowing candidates to prepare in time for the submission of tenders.</seg>
<seg id="87">As a rule, the construction authorities audited complied with this requirement.</seg>
<seg id="88">In isolated cases, errors in the information released, incorrect application of provisions and/or a lack of controls may have impaired competition (item 4.3).</seg>
<seg id="89">There is a greater risk of manipulation when selecting candidates to participate in a restricted procurement procedure.</seg>
<seg id="90">Under EU law, the number of candidates invited must be high enough to guarantee genuine competition.</seg>
<seg id="91">Selection criteria shall be objective, non-discriminatory and published sufficiently in advance.</seg>
<seg id="92">Beyond EU requirements, contracting authorities in both countries should as often as possible rotate candidates who invite participation in the procedure when selecting suppliers.</seg>
<seg id="93">In Germany, there are in part very detailed requirements to prevent the risks of manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="94">In some cases, the audited contracting authorities did not follow these requirements.</seg>
<seg id="95">In the Czech Republic, selection decisions were not always credible (point 4.4).</seg>
<seg id="96">In both countries, contracting authorities must ensure during the procurement process that all candidates wishing to submit a tender receive the same information.</seg>
<seg id="97">Any agreements between these candidates, and between them and third parties involved in the preparation of the specifications, must be avoided as far as possible, so as not to restrict competition through unlawful agreements.</seg>
<seg id="98">In Germany, the measures are more thorough than in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="99">However, the audited German contracting authorities did not meet this requirement in several cases (point 4.5).</seg>
<seg id="100">In both countries, the principle of cross-checking and transparency must be applied when opening envelopes.</seg>
<seg id="101">Labelling, documentation, protection and confidentiality requirements are intended to limit the scope for manipulation and are particularly detailed in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="102">Checks in both countries found only a few cases of irregularities (paragraph 4.6).</seg>
<seg id="103">The assessment and evaluation of bids is regulated procedurally in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="104">The relevant German measures are more comprehensive, but have not always been respected by the audited contracting authorities.</seg>
<seg id="105">For example, contracting authorities passed on their tenders to third parties for inspection without prior assessment, without properly documenting any suspicious circumstances.</seg>
<seg id="106">Thus, offers were insufficiently protected against subsequent manipulation (paragraph 4.7).</seg>
<seg id="107">For the purposes of legal protection, the participants must be informed about the intended contract award before the latter is finalised.</seg>
<seg id="108">This legal protection rule also is designed to prevent corruptive action.</seg>
<seg id="109">The law of the Czech Republic provides for judicial review of contract award procedures also for national tenders.</seg>
<seg id="110">Only in few cases, the notification of the enterprises was not appropriately ensured (item 4.8).</seg>
<seg id="111">The tender documentation was not always complete or fully credible for the audited contracting entities in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="112">In the case of several procurement procedures, transparency requirements applied at European level were not always properly respected in the minutes of the procedure.</seg>
<seg id="113">In addition, some of the weaknesses identified reduced the preventive anti-corruption function of the dossier.</seg>
<seg id="114">Contracting entities in both countries mostly complied with their reporting obligations (paragraph 4.9).</seg>
<seg id="115">Summary of the main principles of European procurement law and the prevention of corruption</seg>
<seg id="116">European tender law</seg>
<seg id="117">In order to ensure free competition in the EU, the European Parliament and the Council of the European Union adopted, inter alia, a Directive on the coordination of procedures for the award of public works contracts, public supply contracts and public service contracts to ensure the free movement of goods and services, and a Directive on the coordination of laws, regulations and administrative provisions relating to review procedures for the award of public supply contracts and public works contracts (the Remedies Directive), both of which were to be transposed into national law.</seg>
<seg id="118">The general EU procurement principles include in particular: a requirement for a competitive environment; a requirement for equal treatment or non-discrimination; a requirement for transparency.</seg>
<seg id="119">EU procurement principles include the Directive on the Coordination of Public Procurement Procedures in addition includes provisions for construction projects with a total foreseeable value of over €5 million.</seg>
<seg id="120">These provisions shall affect: the content of the procurement documents; type of procurement procedure used; disclosure of certain information before, during and after proceedings; compliance with the deadline for the receipt of tenders; the qualification requirements that may be required of tenderers; the criteria for selecting the most suitable tender.</seg>
<seg id="121">The legal protection of candidates is governed by the Remedies Directive.</seg>
<seg id="122">In the event of a potential breach of procurement law, tenderers may have the contracting authority's decision reviewed in accordance with the review procedures.</seg>
<seg id="123">Both countries transposed EU requirements into national legislation.</seg>
<seg id="124">Preventing corruption</seg>
<seg id="125">The importance of preventing corruption</seg>
<seg id="126">There is no legal definition in either country of what corruption actually means.</seg>
<seg id="127">Corruption is widely understood as an abuse of a personal (confidential) position for its own benefit.</seg>
<seg id="128">As a rule, this means that such abuse is encouraged by those benefiting.</seg>
<seg id="129">Corruption can be an obstacle to competition and can cause serious economic losses.</seg>
<seg id="130">Total corruption-related damages are estimated to account for 5% of the world's economic output.</seg>
<seg id="131">For the EU, these costs are estimated at 1% of the EU's economic output.</seg>
<seg id="132">Where a contracting authority is involved, agreements restricting competition or allowing dishonest conduct may undermine confidence in the integrity, ability and overall work of the public administration.</seg>
<seg id="133">That is why preventing corruption is an essential task for contracting authorities.</seg>
<seg id="134">Practice and procedures must be scrutinised, particularly in areas particularly vulnerable to corruption, so that adequate measures can be taken to prevent it.</seg>
<seg id="135">Taking preventive action and carrying out effective controls can substantially reduce the susceptibility of the decision-making process to corruption.</seg>
<seg id="136">As a rule, the award of works contracts is considered to be an area particularly vulnerable to corruption.</seg>
<seg id="137">Measures to prevent corruption</seg>
<seg id="138">In Germany, corruption is prosecutable under criminal and labour law, with particular regard to active and passive bribery, receiving and offering significant benefits.</seg>
<seg id="139">The German federal government has issued a manual of recommendations on the prevention of corruption in the federal administration, according to which the following principles are applied throughout the procurement process outside of risk analysis: preference for open procurement; principle of multiple control and transparent decision-making; separation of planning, procurement and accounting phases; accurate and complete tender documentation.</seg>
<seg id="140">In addition, other measures having a preventive effect against corruption have become part of procurement law.</seg>
<seg id="141">In 2011, the relevant Federal Ministry of Information Technology introduced a system to monitor procurement for the construction of federal roads.</seg>
<seg id="142">Using this system, data such as estimated costs, total contract value and the involvement of private design offices can be fully recorded and analysed to identify any discrepancies.</seg>
<seg id="143">In the Czech Republic, corruption is prosecuted under criminal law, and the level of labour or civil law is also an option.</seg>
<seg id="144">The legal requirement for transparency, equal treatment and non-discrimination throughout the procurement process (preparation and implementation) is the most important part of preventing corruption.</seg>
<seg id="145">Anti-corruption measures in this area were set out by the government in the "Government's Anti-Corruption Strategy 2011-2012" which was updated for 2013 and 2014.</seg>
<seg id="146">Some of these measures have been incorporated into the Public Procurement Act and subsequent implementing legislation.</seg>
<seg id="147">The new legislation contains the following basic provisions: lowering the thresholds for small-scale contracts; the obligation of prior notice by the contracting authority, including the justification for the contract; the prohibition on limiting the number of tenderers in a restricted procedure and the abolition of the general possibility to limit the number of tenderers by drawing lots; obligation to publish contracts, including annexes; obligation to publish actual and lists of subcontractors.</seg>
<seg id="148">Results of controls related to subsequent stages of procurement</seg>
<seg id="149">Tender Documentation</seg>
<seg id="150">Tender documents shall contain all information necessary to enable tenderers to prepare their tenders in an appropriate manner.</seg>
<seg id="151">The documentation shall, in particular, allow for the processing of the offer price.</seg>
<seg id="152">In order to do so, tenderers must not be exposed to risks they could not have anticipated.</seg>
<seg id="153">The tender dossier shall contain, in particular, specifications, as well as requirements to prove the qualifications of the tenderers and criteria for selecting the most advantageous tender.</seg>
<seg id="154">The Requirements of European Law and the Prevention of Corruption</seg>
<seg id="155">In particular, European law contains requirements relating to technical specifications.</seg>
<seg id="156">The specifications must limit competition as little as possible and all interested parties must have equal access to them.</seg>
<seg id="157">Specifications must be neutral.</seg>
<seg id="158">Requirements for specific specific products are permissible on a very limited scale in procurement documents.</seg>
<seg id="159">The basic principle of preventing corruption is that the tender documents do not contain requirements that could restrict competition.</seg>
<seg id="160">Furthermore, documentation should avoid ambiguities or inaccurate data that create scope for speculation and manipulation in the evaluation of tenders.</seg>
<seg id="161">Provisions of German and Czech procurement law</seg>
<seg id="162">Same or similar provisions</seg>
<seg id="163">Both countries have transposed EU legal provisions into their national legislation.</seg>
<seg id="164">The basic principle is that specifications should be given generally without reference to a specific product or brand.</seg>
<seg id="165">The specifications must specify the deliveries and services required and detail the numbers of units of work and deliveries.</seg>
<seg id="166">In normal cases, prices should be indicated by units of work or supply (e.g. in CZK/m or CZK/item).</seg>
<seg id="167">It is permissible to define the work required in terms of functionality only in exceptional cases.</seg>
<seg id="168">In principle, the rule is that specifications must be drawn up completely and unambiguously.</seg>
<seg id="169">They must contain precise quantities and must not include works and supplies, the necessity of which is not obvious.</seg>
