<seg id="685">For many building events, such as university buildings, roads and railways, contracting authorities did not exclude tenderers from participating in a procurement procedure, even though they did not meet the requirements of the contracting authority as set out in the tender specifications, or did not provide evidence of qualification to the extent required, or, conversely, one contracting authority could not substantiate or explain the reason for the exclusion of a candidate who met the requirements.</seg>
<seg id="686">Rating</seg>
<seg id="687">In the case of the construction of a sewage treatment plant, although the various evaluation criteria of the contract award procedure for the contractor were established, they were not respected by the contracting authority during the procedure.</seg>
<seg id="688">For the railway infrastructure development action, the weightings of the award evaluation criteria were not set at the start of the evaluation process, but only at the beginning of the evaluation.</seg>
<seg id="689">For the road repair project, the assessment of the criterion of ‘shortening the construction period’ was not carried out correctly.</seg>
<seg id="690">For second- and third-place bidders, the evaluation incorrectly indicated a greater reduction in construction time than indicated in their bids.</seg>
<seg id="691">Documentation of candidate selection reasons</seg>
<seg id="692">For the three housing promotion actions, the contracting authority did not substantiate on what criteria it assessed the bids received and how it selected the most appropriate of them.</seg>
<seg id="693">The accuracy of the selection of small-scale contractors associated with the construction of a road circuit with an estimated price of up to 500K.</seg>
<seg id="694">The CZK could not be verified, as suppliers were selected only on the basis of telephone consultations on price and delivery date, but no proof of these negotiations was produced.</seg>
<seg id="695">Summary</seg>
<seg id="696">In both countries, the rules for the verification and evaluation of tenders comply with EU requirements.</seg>
<seg id="697">They differ, however, with regard to the specific steps of the procedure and the choice of the individuals involved in the procedure.</seg>
<seg id="698">Unlike the Czech Republic, in Germany these steps of the procurement process are governed by stricter and more detailed requirements, especially as regards the application of the cross-principle and the protection of tenders.</seg>
<seg id="699">The same applies to the rules for verifying the appropriateness of the prices offered.</seg>
<seg id="700">In both countries, it was found in some cases of checks that substantial steps in the process of verifying and evaluating tenders had not been documented at all and, if so, only partially.</seg>
<seg id="701">The lack of control tools and transparency in decision-making during the review and evaluation of tenders allows for manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="702">The inspections showed serious deficiencies, such as the transmission of tenders to third parties without prior proper examination and documentation of tenders by the contracting authority.</seg>
<seg id="703">Where contracting entities entrust a third party with the performance of the functions related to the examination and evaluation of tenders, appropriate measures and increased scrutiny of measures against increased possibility of manipulation are necessary.</seg>
<seg id="704">In checking the legitimacy of the prices, the audited German contracting authorities did not in all cases make use of the complete set of tools available and did not address their own pricing structure.</seg>
<seg id="705">In the Czech Republic, weaknesses were found in the evaluation of the suitability of offers and the use of evaluation criteria.</seg>
<seg id="706">Completion of tender</seg>
<seg id="707">After the tenders have been examined and evaluated, the procurement process is concluded with the award of the contract or the cancellation of the procedure.</seg>
<seg id="708">The Requirements of European Law and the Prevention of Corruption</seg>
<seg id="709">In the case of a European procedure, all tenderers must be informed in advance of the decision to award the contract.</seg>
<seg id="710">Suppliers shall have an opportunity to review the decision taken within a limited period of 10 or 15 days and to request a review if appropriate.</seg>
<seg id="711">THISsegmentISintentionallyLEFTblank</seg>
<seg id="712">The 10-day time limit applies to electronic submissions and 15 days to other submissions.</seg>
<seg id="713">The contract may not be concluded before the expiry of this period or before the review procedure has been decided.</seg>
<seg id="714">If the review body rejects the complaint and upholds the decision, candidates and tenderers must be given the opportunity to have the correctness of the application of the procurement law reviewed by an independent court.</seg>
<seg id="715">This measure ensures that no contracting authority will be able to circumvent the legal protection of contractors by swiftly implementing the award decision.</seg>
<seg id="716">The contracting authority must document the progress of the procedure appropriately.</seg>
<seg id="717">Provisions of German and Czech procurement law</seg>
<seg id="718">Same or similar provisions</seg>
<seg id="719">Both countries have implemented management information obligations.</seg>
<seg id="720">In both countries, the final decision on the outcome of the procurement procedure rests with the contracting authority.</seg>
<seg id="721">However, it cannot arbitrarily deviate from the results of a properly conducted screening and evaluation.</seg>
<seg id="722">The contracting authority is to conclude the contract at the specified time.</seg>
<seg id="723">This is because after this deadline the bidder is not bound by its bid.</seg>
<seg id="724">The contract content must not deviate from the winning bid.</seg>
<seg id="725">Unsuccessful tenderers are to be informed of the result in good time, stating the reason why their tender has not been accepted.</seg>
<seg id="726">Cancellation of the procurement procedure is permissible only if certain conditions are met, e.g. if the prices in the tenders do not comply with the specifications.</seg>
<seg id="727">Different provisions</seg>
<seg id="728">In the Czech Republic, the mandatory waiting time before the conclusion of a contract of 10 or 15 days applies to both European and national procedures.</seg>
<seg id="729">In Germany, the equivalent provision applies only to European proceedings.</seg>
<seg id="730">In all other procedures in Germany, tenderers cannot be informed of the award of the contract before a decision is taken on its EU provisions and review award.</seg>
<seg id="731">In the Czech Republic, the tender procedure must be cancelled if a single tender was received or only one tender met the requirements for its consideration and evaluation.</seg>
<seg id="732">In Germany, a contract must be awarded even if a single tender has been received, provided that the tender meets the conditions set out in the tender specifications and is cost-effective.</seg>
<seg id="733">Main control findings</seg>
<seg id="734">BRH</seg>
<seg id="735">The inspections found few inconsistencies in the completion of the audited procurement processes.</seg>
<seg id="736">In some instances of European proceedings, the enabling companies received letters before the reporting deadline, which may invalidate the contract.</seg>
<seg id="737">Also, in several cases of open procedures, letters of authorisation contained modifications incompatible with the tender content, e.g. new deadlines.</seg>
<seg id="738">In some cases, contracting authorities did not meet the award deadlines.</seg>
<seg id="739">In one open procedure, the contracting authority selected the second most advantageous tender because a tenderer offering a price more than 50% lower no longer wished to perform the contract at the price originally offered.</seg>
<seg id="740">OWN</seg>
<seg id="741">In the refurbishment and construction of the college, in one case the contracting authority did not conclude a works contract with the contractor in accordance with the draft contract contained in the tender of the successful tenderer.</seg>
<seg id="742">For some road repair and maintenance operations, the construction of the motorway and the ring road, contracts were concluded later than the statute.</seg>
<seg id="743">For construction works in former military tours, the contracting authority sent a notice of selection of the most suitable tender to all tenderers after the statutory deadline.</seg>
<seg id="744">Summary</seg>
<seg id="745">Both countries have implemented EU rules on the termination of procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="746">Legal protection for failed candidates contributes to curbing corruption.</seg>
<seg id="747">The Czech Public Procurement Law includes the Institute of Legal Protection even in cases of contracts below EU limits.</seg>
<seg id="748">In both countries, it was found that the limited time limit for concluding a contract was exceeded.</seg>
<seg id="749">This can cause adverse economic consequences and increase the risk of manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="750">In the future, contracting authorities should eliminate such shortcomings when concluding procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="751">Documentation, notifications, information obligations</seg>
<seg id="752">The procurement process, with all its stages, relevant findings and decisions, including relevant justifications, shall be documented in a transparent manner.</seg>
<seg id="753">The completion of the procurement process at European level must be published.</seg>
<seg id="754">The data on procurement procedures are summarised in EU statistics.</seg>
<seg id="755">The Requirements of European Law and the Prevention of Corruption</seg>
<seg id="756">The obligation to document procurement procedures is in line with the fundamental requirement of the EU-wide principle of transparency.</seg>
<seg id="757">Only proper and time-relevant documentation on decision-making and justification gives a guarantee of transparency in the procurement process and, above all, guarantees effective legal protection of the interests of each tenderer in cases where the value of the contract exceeds the European limits.</seg>
<seg id="758">Proper documentation is also an essential part of anti-corruption measures, as the obligation to provide detailed justification for individual decisions and their justification significantly reduces the scope for manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="759">In cases of European procurement procedures, the contracting authority must notify the completion of these procedures to the EU's Office of Official Publications within 48 days of the date of award of the contract.</seg>
<seg id="760">The Office publishes the notice in the Official Journal of the EU and this also fulfils the transparency requirement.</seg>
<seg id="761">The contracting authority must summarise the essential details of its procurement procedures and communicate them to the European Commission through the relevant national ministries.</seg>
<seg id="762">On this basis, the European Commission produces annual statistics to provide an overview of the development of the single market in the field of construction.</seg>
<seg id="763">Provisions of German and Czech procurement law</seg>
<seg id="764">Same or similar provisions</seg>
<seg id="765">Both countries fully transposed into their national legislation the provisions of the European law on documentation and notification obligations.</seg>
<seg id="766">The provisions on documentation and notification for European statistics purposes are almost identical in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="767">Different provisions</seg>
<seg id="768">In the Czech Republic, the obligation to notify the award of a contract applies not only to European procedures, but also to national procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="769">The notice period is only 15 days from the conclusion of the contract.</seg>
<seg id="770">In Germany, the obligation to notify procurement procedures, in addition to those which are mandatory under European law, applies only to restricted procedures exceeding the limit of €25K (£625K) and direct procedures exceeding the limit of €15K (£375K) including VAT.</seg>
<seg id="771">Only interested parties are informed below this limit.</seg>
<seg id="772">Main control findings</seg>
<seg id="773">BRH</seg>
<seg id="774">Documentation</seg>
<seg id="775">A large number of the terms of reference were not fully documented.</seg>
<seg id="776">The notification did not contain all the necessary information, e.g. reasons for the supply specifications and national rules.</seg>
<seg id="777">In one case, the contracting authority did not explain why it had contracted a tenderer whose tender did not include mandatory particulars.</seg>
<seg id="778">In several cases, some required records were also missing.</seg>
<seg id="779">Award Publication</seg>
<seg id="780">In the case of some European procedures, the contracting authority erred in the publication of the notice.</seg>
<seg id="781">In several of the terms of reference, there was no evidence of publication of the notice.</seg>
<seg id="782">Notification obligation</seg>
<seg id="783">The statistically cleared files included the required minimum of information and were created and sent on time.</seg>
<seg id="784">Preliminary transparency</seg>
<seg id="785">In most cases, the procuring entity disclosed the contract result.</seg>
<seg id="786">In the case of one sponsor, contract information was not disclosed due to a communication error.</seg>
<seg id="787">It took the contracting authority six months to notice the error.</seg>
<seg id="788">Consequently, the outcome of the proceedings was not disclosed during that period.</seg>
<seg id="789">OWN</seg>
<seg id="790">Documentation</seg>
<seg id="791">For events related to the organisation of a major sporting event, significant shortcomings in the documentation of the tender process were identified, such as incorrect bidding price data in the evaluation committee's meeting protocols.</seg>
<seg id="792">In addition, some of the documents opening the envelopes were not signed.</seg>
<seg id="793">Award Publication</seg>
<seg id="794">In preparation for the repair and maintenance of the roads, the construction of the motorway and the road circuit, the contract award notices were sent after the deadline or were not published.</seg>
<seg id="795">Summary</seg>
<seg id="796">Provisions on documentation and notification and notification obligations include European requirements and are almost identical in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="797">This generally ensures the transparency of procurement procedures and final selection.</seg>
<seg id="798">The Czech reporting obligations are somewhat stricter compared to the German ones.</seg>
<seg id="799">The checks revealed shortcomings substantially reducing the value of the dossier as a means of preventing corruption.</seg>
<seg id="800">THISsegmentISintentionallyLEFTblank</seg>
<seg id="801">Contracting entities should continue to enhance the transparency of their procurement procedures and fully comply with reporting and notification requirements.</seg>
<seg id="802">Summary evaluation and recommendations</seg>
<seg id="803">Parallel audits of the SAO and BRH focused on two areas that are essential for the public procurement process in both the Czech Republic and Germany, namely the application of EU procurement law and the prevention of corruption.</seg>
<seg id="804">EU legislation provides an opportunity for international competition within the EU to create a single European market.</seg>
<seg id="805">Measures to prevent corruption are not only intended to avoid it or at least to reduce it, but also to prevent financial damage and possible loss of confidence in the integrity of government.</seg>
<seg id="806">The audit findings of the two audit institutions - the SAO and BRH - with regard to the application of the two countries' procurement law and the comparison of its respective provisions give an inside view of the common and different elements that may assist the two countries in the further development and application of this law.</seg>
<seg id="807">Application of EU procurement law</seg>
<seg id="808">Both countries transposed EU procurement law into their national legislation.</seg>
<seg id="809">There is thus an important common base in both countries for public procurement and the fulfilment of basic requirements in the area of: competition; equal treatment of candidates; transparency of procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="810">Contracting authorities reinforce these requirements in part with very extensive measures.</seg>
<seg id="811">The Czech Republic has extended public procurement provisions requiring a European procedure to procedures that are below EU limits and are therefore governed by national legislation.</seg>
<seg id="812">Nevertheless, checks have shown that contracting authorities are not always fully compliant with all relevant provisions of EU requirements.</seg>
<seg id="813">German contracting authorities should continue to improve the quality of their procurement procedures in order to eliminate the irregularities mentioned, taking into account the implementation of EU requirements.</seg>
<seg id="814">In the Czech Republic, the controls identified risks affecting economy and achieving value for money.</seg>
<seg id="815">These include, in particular, an incomplete definition of the subject-matter of the contract, which resulted in additional works often awarded in breach of the law, a lack of definition of the price envisaged, and the requisite qualifications, which narrowed down the potential pool of tenderers and thus reduced competition, particularly in the field of transport works.</seg>
<seg id="816">Preventing corruption</seg>
<seg id="817">The joint inspections were not aimed at detecting cases of corruption.</seg>
<seg id="818">The reason was that both BRH and the SAO did not have sufficient tools to do so.</seg>
<seg id="819">They can nevertheless examine whether the competent authorities of both countries are taking measures to curb corruption and manipulation in public procurement and how these measures are applied.</seg>
<seg id="820">In terms of preventing corruption, the two countries have focused on different aspects.</seg>
<seg id="821">Above all, German provisions give room for broad and unrestricted competition, transparency, and controls as a central element in preventing corruption.</seg>
<seg id="822">The Czech regulations are mainly aimed at enhancing the transparency of procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="823">BRH</seg>
<seg id="824">In Germany, there are general principles for preventing corruption that apply to the entire federal administration.</seg>
<seg id="825">These principles have also been incorporated into the requirements of public procurement and have been adopted to meet the specific needs of such procurement.</seg>
<seg id="826">The relevant provisions specify, at times with great precision, the ways of complying with the requirements to prevent corruption during the procurement process and the choice of the people included therein.</seg>
<seg id="827">In the BRH's view, the principle of preference for open procurement procedures and calls for participation is a particularly appropriate tool to substantially reduce the risk of corruption in public procurement, while limiting competition increases the risk of manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="828">Risk analysis and adequate controls (in particular the principle of cross-checking), transparency requirements, procurement documents and various organisational measures are also effective mechanisms for preventing corruption and manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="829">The BRH therefore does not feel the need for substantial changes to the current provisions that public institutions must comply with when awarding public contracts.</seg>
<seg id="830">Anti-corruption measures are widely applied in practice.</seg>
<seg id="831">Irregularities found in some areas have highlighted weaknesses in compliance with some requirements.</seg>
<seg id="832">Therefore, contracting authorities should provide further training to their staff, familiarising them with anti-corruption requirements and further raising their awareness in this area.</seg>
<seg id="833">A significant proportion of the weaknesses identified relate to activities delegated by the construction administration to private entrepreneurs.</seg>
<seg id="834">However, the absence of adequate controls in the delegation of powers increases the risk of abuse.</seg>
<seg id="835">Activities susceptible to manipulation and corruption should therefore only be transferred to third parties if the administration can guarantee a sufficient degree of protection against unauthorised interference.</seg>
<seg id="836">OWN</seg>
<seg id="837">In the Czech Republic, anti-corruption strategies have been adopted at government level, affecting the area of public procurement in a significant way.</seg>
<seg id="838">The audit actions of the SAO took place during the period of implementation of one of the most important parts of this strategy, namely a significant amendment of the Public Procurement Act and the adoption of the subsequent implementing regulations.</seg>
<seg id="839">The strategy adopted and the new statutory provisions can be effective steps to improve the situation.</seg>
<seg id="840">Under the new rules, the contracting authority must, for example, justify the effectiveness of the contract, establish the anticipated value of the contract, the adequacy of the requirements for qualifications, establish the basic evaluation criteria and the way tenders are evaluated, and properly document and publish everything.</seg>
<seg id="841">Recommendations</seg>
<seg id="842">Overall, both the SAO and BRH have a favourable opinion of the ways in which EU requirements are implemented.</seg>
<seg id="843">Their broad application in practice has confirmed that EU requirements for competition, equal treatment and transparency form an appropriate basis for public procurement within the EU.</seg>
<seg id="844">The supranational model, established in the EU, can also serve as a base for similar projects aimed at facilitating and promoting international competition.</seg>
<seg id="845">Taking into account the great potential for material and non-material damage resulting from manipulation and corruption in connection with public procurement, both BRH and the SAO insist that it is the responsibility of the contracting authorities to continue and improve measures against corruption and manipulation where possible.</seg>
<seg id="846">In particular, organisational structures and procurement processes should be continuously monitored for weaknesses and risks to identify and respond appropriately to the need for remedial action.</seg>
<seg id="847">Compared to the practice in Germany, it has emerged that the share of open procurement procedures should be increased in the Czech Republic, giving room for competition and substantially reducing the possibility of corrupt behaviour.</seg>
<seg id="848">Parcel procurement may also have a positive impact on the price achieved in cases where this is permissible and appropriate for the contracting authority. The higher number of bidders puts pressure on the price achieved.</seg>
<seg id="849">Ensuring its organisation also has an influence on the conduct of the procurement process.</seg>
<seg id="850">In Germany, it is provided by special state organisations, while in the Czech Republic, with the exception of transport structures, it is organised by the central authorities themselves or through contracting organisations.</seg>
<seg id="851">Both the SAO and BRH wish to further develop the knowledge in their work where appropriate and to address it with their parliament and government beyond their joint project.</seg>
<seg id="852">Moreover, they believe that the principles of procurement law and its implementation, as described in this report, will also be of interest at the level of the International Organisation of Supreme Audit Institutions (INTOSAI), as these principles and findings are of general importance to effectively tackle corruption and to ensure that public contracts are awarded under a regime of well-functioning and fair competition and that value for money is achieved.</seg>
