<p>
<seg id="1">JOINT FINAL REPORT on the Results of Parallel Controls on the Administration of Excise Duties in the Slovak Republic and the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="2">Joint final report</seg>
<seg id="3">May 2017</seg>
<seg id="4">Supreme Audit Office of the Slovak Republic</seg>
<seg id="5">Supreme Audit Office of the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="6">Introduction Word</seg>
<seg id="7">The submitted joint report reports on the progress and outcome of international cooperation in parallel controls carried out by the Supreme Audit Office of the Slovak Republic and the Supreme Audit Office of the Czech Republic, focusing on excise management in 2012-2015.</seg>
<seg id="8">The cooperation between the supreme audit institutions of the two countries was carried out on the basis of a cooperation agreement between the SAO of the Slovak Republic and the SAO of the Czech Republic in the execution of parallel controls aimed at the management of excise duties, which was concluded in August 2015.</seg>
<seg id="9">The topic of parallel controls was chosen based on the fact that the two EU Member States are based on common European legislation in order to see how it is applied at national level, how the system of excise management is set up and how the systems in the SR and the CR differ.</seg>
<seg id="10">The greatest benefits of the control actions carried out were in exchanging experience, identifying differences and identifying good practice.</seg>
<seg id="11">Last but not least, the benefit of finding that international comparability of data on the performance and efficiency of excise administration is very limited without parallel controls.</seg>
<seg id="12">Miloslav Kala,</seg>
<seg id="13">Karol Mitrík,</seg>
<seg id="14">President</seg>
<seg id="15">President</seg>
<seg id="16">Supreme Audit Office of the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="17">Supreme Audit Office of the Slovak Republic</seg>
<seg id="18">about the results of parallel controls of the SPD administration in SR and CR</seg>
<seg id="19">Summary and evaluation</seg>
<seg id="20">The legislation on excise duties in the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic and their administration is in line with EU legislation and significantly exceeds EU requirements.</seg>
<seg id="21">Differences have been identified between the adjustment of excise duties in the Slovak Republic and the Czech Republic; in the Czech Republic, the verification of the economic stability of applicants for the issuance of permits and the mandatory marking and colouring of selected mineral oils and certain other oils contribute to the efficient administration of excise duties; In SR, the distribution of control stamps is simpler than in the Czech Republic and less burdensome for tax authorities.</seg>
<seg id="22">In the fight against evasion of excise duties, supervision of the movement of raw tobacco or tobacco raw material, the implementation of the fuel distributor institute and the registration of sellers of consumer alcohol packaging have proved good practice in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="23">Revenue from excise duties in the SR and the Czech Republic is growing more slowly than other tax revenues.</seg>
<seg id="24">The EU's objectives of reducing labour taxation, introducing eco-saving measures and reducing dependence on tobacco and alcohol have not yet been met in the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic, inter alia because there is no indexation of excise rates in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="25">This has the effect of reducing the materiality of excise duties in total tax revenues and, as a result of increasing purchasing power, a real reduction in the tax burden of excise duties.</seg>
<seg id="26">The introduction of environmental measures has long been financially supported by the state, but the measures have a negative impact on excise revenue, which will thus need to be replaced in the future by other revenues or by a reduction in the state's spending.</seg>
<seg id="27">Administrative expenditure incurred to manage excise duties in both the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic has been growing over the long term, mainly due to wage increases, and their efficiency has been declining.</seg>
<seg id="28">In the SR, this efficiency is also negatively affected by expenditure on the computerisation of excise administration (IT expenditure) and expenditure incurred on wages of employees performing permanent tax supervision in alcohol tax warehouses.</seg>
<seg id="29">The electronisation of excise administration in SR has not had a significant effect on the reduction in the number of tax administrations.</seg>
<seg id="30">The SAO of the Czech Republic and the SAO of the Slovak Republic recommend that the FŘ SR reconsider the merits of the exercise of permanent tax supervision in tax warehouses on ethyl alcohol.</seg>
<seg id="31">In the Czech Republic, the efficiency of administrative expenditure was affected by the fact that the Customs Administration of the Czech Republic did not apply procedures during the audited period which would have led to a reduction in the personnel intensity of excise administration.</seg>
<seg id="32">The number of comparable administrative actions of tax administrations was similar in the Slovak Republic and the Czech Republic in the different years of the audited period, while the number of comparable tax entities in the Slovak Republic is about a third lower than in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="33">Tax administrators in the Slovak Republic perform administrative tasks mainly in the form of physical exercise of tax supervision, while tax administrators in the Czech Republic emphasize remote supervision and risk analysis.</seg>
<seg id="34">The management of excise duties in the Slovak Republic is more administratively demanding than in the Czech Republic and, given the ratio of the number of tax operations to the number of entities, more costly.</seg>
<seg id="35">The electronisation of excise administration in the Slovak Republic and the Czech Republic took place in different areas.</seg>
<seg id="36">In the Slovak Republic, the administration of excise tax returns is fully electronised; in the Czech Republic, documents proving the taxation of selected products in free tax circulation are transmitted electronically.</seg>
<seg id="37">Both methods of electronisation promote the efficient management of excise duties and therefore the SAO of the Czech Republic and the SAO of the Slovak Republic recommend applying them not only in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="38">The total expenditure for the introduction of the EMCS could not be compared as the PSR only provided expenditure data for the upgrade of the system in the period 2011-2015, but the expenditure was also made before this period.</seg>
<seg id="39">The expenses incurred in that period only for the upgrade of EMCS were about 20% higher in SR than those incurred in the Czech Republic both for the introduction of EMCS and for the upgrade of this system over more than a decade.</seg>
<seg id="40">Excise tax managers in the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic did not achieve comparable values of quality indicators when spending comparably.</seg>
<seg id="41">The level of surveillance is comparable in both countries, but in the SR, the management of excise duties is significantly more resource-intensive.</seg>
<seg id="42">The introduction of the Electronic System for Monitoring the Movement of Excise Products (EMCS) has made excise tax administration more efficient, but lower in the SR as significantly higher expenditure was spent on the introduction of the system and its modernisation than in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="43">Basic information</seg>
<seg id="44">The cooperation of the two audit institutions was carried out under the Cooperation Treaty in carrying out parallel controls on the management of excise duties on 18.8.2015.</seg>
<seg id="45">The SAO of the Czech Republic and the SAO of the Slovak Republic agreed to carry out parallel checks, primarily focused on issues of excise administration, the results of which will allow analysis, mutual comparison and evaluation of the findings.</seg>
<seg id="46">Joint audit questions were agreed on which the parallel controls were based.</seg>
<seg id="47">Subject characteristics and objectives of parallel control:</seg>
<seg id="48">The aim of the parallel controls was to compare the performance of excise managers, taking into account qualitative and quantitative indicators, and to identify weaknesses in the excise management process.</seg>
<seg id="49">In particular, the following main audit questions were to be answered:</seg>
<seg id="50">Did excise tax managers in the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic achieve comparable values of quality indicators when spending comparably?</seg>
<seg id="51">Has the introduction of the Electronic Excise Movement and Control System (EMCS) made excise administration more efficient and has the expenditure to introduce it been expedient?</seg>
<seg id="52">Parallel checks should have identified the causes of significant differences affecting the efficiency and effectiveness of the tax administration in the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic, especially in the regulatory and organisational structure setting.</seg>
<seg id="53">THISsegmentISintentionallyLEFTblank</seg>
<seg id="54">The Directorate-General for Customs (DG) and the Financial Directorate of the Slovak Republic (DG SR) have joined the Joint Declaration on Cooperation between the Visegrad Four countries, the objectives of the Declaration include the areas of excise duties including, inter alia, the fight against fraud, exploring the possibility of harmonising legislation and seeking harmonised interpretations on the rules of selected problems, exploring the possibility of joint activities to increase efficiency in detecting fraud and sharing experiences and best practices.</seg>
<seg id="55">1 The EMCS is operated under Decision No 1152/2003/EC of the European Parliament and of the Council of 16 June 2003 on computerising the movement and surveillance of excisable products.</seg>
<seg id="56">Identification of the audit carried out by the SAO of the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="57">Check number: 15/33</seg>
<seg id="58">Subject of control: Administration of excise duties</seg>
<seg id="59">Objective of the audit: The aim of the audit of the SAO of the Czech Republic was to examine the customs authorities' procedure for the administration of excise duties, in particular for the monitoring of shipments in the system of conditional exemption from excise duties and for securing tax (customs debts); verify that the excise management system is set up to ensure the efficiency of state budget revenue collection.</seg>
<seg id="60">Period audited: 2012-2015 and, in case of factual context, the period before and after</seg>
<seg id="61">Controlled Person: Directorate-General of Customs</seg>
<seg id="62">Identification of the inspection carried out by the SAO SR</seg>
<seg id="63">Check number: KA-023/2016/1050</seg>
<seg id="64">Subject of control: Administration of excise duties</seg>
<seg id="65">Objective of the inspection: The aim of the inspection was an independent and objective examination of whether the FŘ SR and the customs offices (CA) operate economically, efficiently and effectively in accordance with universally binding legislation in the management of excise duties.</seg>
<seg id="66">Controlled period: years 2012-2015</seg>
