<p>
<seg id="1">Report on the results of the parallel review of the administration of value added tax carried out in the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany</seg>
<seg id="2">Introduction Word</seg>
<seg id="3">The Lima Declaration of 1977 stresses that the supreme audit institutions (SAIs) have the power to audit all public financial operations.</seg>
<seg id="4">The Declaration calls for tax revenues to be controlled to the fullest extent possible.</seg>
<seg id="5">The European Organisation of Supreme Audit Institutions (EUROSAI) considers tax as one of the most significant components of public revenue.</seg>
<seg id="6">The VIth EUROSAI Congress, held in Bonn in 2005, dealt with SAI audits of public revenues.</seg>
<seg id="7">A major step towards optimising SAI control activity is the development of a specific strategy for auditing public revenue.</seg>
<seg id="8">This is particularly relevant to taxes as the bulkiest source of public revenue, most vulnerable to large losses.</seg>
<seg id="9">As national economies become increasingly interconnected and dependent, SAIs may to some extent be unable to carry out control activities without the cooperation of another State's SAI.</seg>
<seg id="10">An example is the audit of internationally organised fraud, which causes substantial losses in revenue for many countries.</seg>
<seg id="11">In order to combat this crime, the responsible authorities need to cooperate with each other.</seg>
<seg id="12">The SAIs that carry out inspections in this area must be willing to establish closer cooperation between themselves.</seg>
<seg id="13">It was at the VIth EUROSAI Congress in Bonn that the idea arose of carrying out a review of the administration of value added tax (VAT) and the VIES system within the framework of cooperation between the Supreme Audit Office and the Federal Court of Auditors, the Bundesrechnungshof.</seg>
<seg id="14">Careful preparation ensued, with both parties first having to familiarise themselves with the legal environment and procedures for managing VAT in the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany.</seg>
<seg id="15">Analysis of this information led to a selection of control topics to be included in the control programme.</seg>
<seg id="16">Achieving an efficient and efficient VAT administration has been a long-standing problem and individual states (in particular the Member States of the European Union) are looking for solutions to improve the system, simplify and make the collection of this tax more transparent.</seg>
<seg id="17">We believe that the results of our scrutiny can serve not only to improve the work of tax administrations, but also as a basis for a proposal to improve the system of international exchange of information.</seg>
<seg id="18">Report on the results of parallel controls on the administration of value added tax carried out in the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany</seg>
<seg id="19">Introduction</seg>
<seg id="20">Control number: (CZ) 06/27 (D) VIII 2 - 2005 - 1215</seg>
<seg id="21">Object of control:</seg>
<seg id="22">(CZ) Value Added Tax Administration after the Czech Republic's accession to the European Union</seg>
<seg id="23">(D) Examination of administrative cooperation in the field of value added tax under Council Regulation (EC) No 1798/2003 and Commission Regulation (EC) No 1925/2004</seg>
<seg id="24">Target of control:</seg>
<seg id="25">(CZ) The objective of the audit operation in the Czech Republic was to examine the procedure of the tax authorities in the administration of value added tax following the integration of the Czech Republic into the single internal market of the European Union (EU) linked to the free movement of goods and services and to examine the use of the VIES system, in particular when checking the exercise of the right to value added tax exemption for intra-Community supplies.</seg>
<seg id="26">(D) The aim of the audit was to examine the system for checking intra-Community value added tax, with a particular focus on administrative cooperation in the field of value added tax under the aforementioned regulations.</seg>
<seg id="27">The result should be a report on weaknesses and recommendations for their elimination.</seg>
<seg id="28">The system of exchange of information on value added tax The auditing actions were carried out by the Supreme Audit Office, the Czech Republic (hereinafter referred to as the SAO) and the German Bundesrechnungshof (hereinafter referred to as BRH) in mutual cooperation on the basis of a contract concluded between the two auditing institutions on 8 June 2006.</seg>
<seg id="29">Cooperation focused mainly on examining selected business transactions carried out between payers from the Czech Republic (the Czech Republic) and the Federal Republic of Germany (the Federal Republic of Germany (the Federal Republic of Germany), using information obtained through international cooperation between tax administrations and comparing the VAT administration systems of the two countries.</seg>
<seg id="30">The joint final report on the results of the control actions was prepared in the sense of the European Directive No 31 for the implementation of the INTOSAI audit standards.</seg>
<seg id="31">The audited period covered the period from 1.5.2004 to 31.12.2005.</seg>
<seg id="32">Summary of results and evaluation of parallel control actions</seg>
<seg id="33">The parallel control in the field of VAT administration in the Czech Republic and the German Republic was carried out on the basis of a contract between the two SAIs.</seg>
<seg id="34">Beyond the main point - the exchange of information under Council Regulation (EC) No 1798/2003 and Commission Regulation (EC) No 1925/2004 - the control covered other topics, such as the registration of payers, VAT returns and recapitulative statements, which are closely linked to the main point.</seg>
<seg id="35">In addition, the control included the legal situation of international bus passenger services and a comparison of some statistical data.</seg>
<seg id="36">Comparing the VAT management systems of the two countries revealed differences in the following areas:</seg>
<seg id="37">1) Registration for VAT.</seg>
<seg id="38">While in Germany, entrepreneurs are registered regardless of their turnover, in the Czech Republic, the primary criterion (among others) for registering is exceeding the limit laid down in the VAT Act.</seg>
<seg id="39">In the Czech Republic, payers are assigned only one tax identification number, which they also use in intra-Community transactions.</seg>
<seg id="40">In Germany, taxpayers are given a tax number when registering for VAT, which only serves for commercial transactions in the territory of Germany.</seg>
<seg id="41">If a German payer intends to carry out intra-Community transactions, it must request the allocation of a special identification number, the so-called VAT ID.</seg>
<seg id="42">As different ways of registering cause problems, conditions should be levelled out across the EU (see 4.1).</seg>
<seg id="43">2) International bus passenger transport.</seg>
<seg id="44">In the Czech Republic, international bus transport of persons is exempt from VAT with the right to deduct VAT.</seg>
<seg id="45">In Germany, the part of the transport that takes place on German territory is subject to VAT.</seg>
<seg id="46">Efforts should be made at EU level to harmonise the situation within the meaning of Article 393 of Council Directive 2006/112/EC on the common system of VAT (see 4.2)</seg>
<seg id="47">3) VAT returns.</seg>
<seg id="48">While in the Czech Republic, taxpayers only submit VAT returns for individual tax years (month or quarter), in Germany, taxpayers are obliged to submit so-called preliminary VAT returns (monthly or quarterly) and must submit annual VAT returns after the end of the calendar year.</seg>
<seg id="49">Unlike CR payers, payers in Germany are required to submit preliminary tax returns electronically.</seg>
<seg id="50">The introduction of the obligation to submit VAT returns electronically in the Czech Republic would increase the efficiency of the Czech tax administration (see 4.3).</seg>
<seg id="51">4) Summary reports.</seg>
<seg id="52">While in the Czech Republic, payers file summary reports at financial offices, in Germany, payers file summary reports at CLOs.</seg>
<seg id="53">The tax authorities in the Czech Republic therefore have the data from the recapitulative statements immediately after they are filed.</seg>
<seg id="54">The information from the recapitulative statements is only available to the German tax authorities once they have been processed into CLOs.</seg>
<seg id="55">Combating VAT fraud requires updated information on intra-Community transactions to be available as soon as possible.</seg>
<seg id="56">Monthly reporting of recapitulative statements would reduce the time lag between the transaction date and the update of the VIES data.</seg>
<seg id="57">This in turn would allow for a timely examination of taxation in the purchaser's Member State (see 4.4).</seg>
<seg id="58">Which would, but would require all Member States to adopt the same deadline for submitting a recapitulative statement.</seg>
<seg id="59">(5) International VAT Information Exchange.</seg>
<seg id="60">The Czech CLO monitors compliance with the three-month deadline for the information requests received.</seg>
<seg id="61">The German CLO does not track the elapsed time.</seg>
<seg id="62">As a result, the German tax authorities dealt with a significantly lower percentage of applications received within the time allowed.</seg>
<seg id="63">Because of these problems, the BRH recommended that the German CLO carry out a permanent warning (see 4.6).</seg>
<seg id="64">6) Risk management system.</seg>
<seg id="65">Each of the two Member States is developing its own risk management system (RMS), which has its strengths and weaknesses.</seg>
<seg id="66">The SAO and BRH point out that an effective RMS cannot be developed by just one Member State.</seg>
<seg id="67">Successful RMS criteria, components and approaches must be exchanged and implemented in every EU Member State, otherwise fraudsters will choose the Member State with the weakest RMS (see 5).</seg>
<seg id="68">In the framework of cooperation, the two SAIs examined selected cases of intra-Community transactions, carried out between tax entities from the Czech Republic and the CFN.</seg>
<seg id="69">Together, thirty-one cases of commercial transactions where there were doubts about their execution or suspicions of VAT evasion were examined using the CLO legislation.</seg>
<seg id="70">It was found that:</seg>
<seg id="71">In some cases, the tax authorities used information obtained through international cooperation to calculate the taxpayer's VAT liability.</seg>
<seg id="72">In those cases, the payers either improperly claimed exemption from VAT on the supply or failed to declare the acquisition of the goods on the VAT return.</seg>
<seg id="73">In some cases, the financial authorities could not use the information obtained because the information was either incomplete or incomprehensible.</seg>
<seg id="74">In other cases, the information could not be used due to different legal provisions in both Member States.</seg>
<seg id="75">In some cases, the tax administration of another Member State refused to respond to a request for information.</seg>
<seg id="76">Cases have been identified where payers have erroneously reported business transactions in summary reports.</seg>
<seg id="77">As a result, the data in VIES was incorrect and the tax administrations had to examine these cases (see 6).</seg>
<seg id="78">Control Action Progress</seg>
<seg id="79">Conduct of the audit operation in the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="80">The audit was carried out between June 2006 and March 2007 by Division II - the revenue division of the state budget and territorial departments of Central Bohemia, northwest Bohemia, southern Bohemia, southern Moravia, central Moravia and northern Moravia.</seg>
<seg id="81">The audited persons were: the Ministry of Finance (hereinafter ‘MF’) and 10 tax offices – the Financial Office in Humpolci, the Financial Office in Jihlava, the Financial Office in Kadani, the Financial Office in Liberec, the Financial Office in Nymburk, the Financial Office in Otrokovice, the Financial Office for Prague 1, the Financial Office for Prague 4 the Financial Office in Sokolova and the Financial Office in Thirti.</seg>
