<p>
<seg id="1">Report on the outcome of international cooperation in checks on the management of excise duties between the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic in 2006</seg>
<seg id="2">Introduction Word</seg>
<seg id="3">The submitted joint report reports on the progress and outcome of international cooperation in parallel controls carried out by the Supreme Audit Office, the Czech Republic and the Najvyšší kontrolný úrad Slovenskej republiky, aimed at the management of excise duties in the period after the accession of the two countries to the European Union.</seg>
<seg id="4">The cooperation was carried out on the basis of a contract for cooperation in control activities, concluded in February 2006.</seg>
<seg id="5">The topic of parallel controls was chosen in view of the fundamental change in the system for collecting excise duties which has taken place in the context of the integration of the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic into the internal market of the European Union since 1 May 2004.</seg>
<seg id="6">The functioning of the European Union's internal market requires the free movement of goods, including excise goods.</seg>
<seg id="7">The basic principle is to allow goods not subject to tax to circulate until the day they are delivered for final consumption.</seg>
<seg id="8">In accordance with that principle, the new legislation, adopted in both countries, allows the movement of goods under tax supervision under a conditional exemption scheme.</seg>
<seg id="9">The system places great demands on tax administrations and foresees close interaction between the competent administrations of the Member States in the fight against tax fraud in this area.</seg>
<seg id="10">Report on the outcome of international cooperation on controls of excise administration for the period 1 May 2004 to 31 December 2005 1.</seg>
<seg id="11">Introduction</seg>
<seg id="12">Check Number: (Czech Republic) 05/34 (SR) 48/11</seg>
<seg id="13">Subject of inspection: (Czech Republic) Excise Management (SR) Procedure of colné orgánov pri správe spotrebá tax</seg>
<seg id="14">The Supreme Audit Office, the Czech Republic (hereinafter referred to as the SAO-CR) and the Najvyšší kontrolný úrad Slovenskej republiky (hereinafter referred to as the SAO of the Slovak Republic) concluded on 8 February 2006 the ‘Contract on Cooperation in Audit Activity’.</seg>
<seg id="15">The subject of the contract was cooperation in parallel checks ‘Administration of Excise Duties’, included in the SAO-CR's 2005 audit work plan under No 05/34, and ‘Control of the progress of colné orgánov in administering rebrebrebrebrebate taxes’, included in the SAO SR's 2006 audit work plan under No 48/11.</seg>
<seg id="16">The parallel checks were in the nature of coordinated checks.</seg>
<seg id="17">The cooperation consisted of exchanging information that could not be obtained by the contracting parties when checking the management of excise duties on their national territory and producing a joint final report on the outcome of the checks within the meaning of the European implementing directives for the implementation of the INTOSAI audit standards - Directive No 31.</seg>
<seg id="18">In the territory of the Czech Republic, control groups from the State Budget Department and the territorial departments of central Bohemia, southern Bohemia, western Bohemia, northwest Bohemia, northeastern Bohemia, southern Moravia, central Moravia and northern Moravia carried out inspections between 7 February and 2 June 2006.</seg>
<seg id="19">27 inspectors were involved in the inspection.</seg>
<seg id="20">The persons audited were the Directorate General of Customs (DG) and 11 tax authorities.</seg>
<seg id="21">Within the DG, 12 selected customs offices were audited out of a total of 54.</seg>
<seg id="22">The audit in the territory of the Slovak Republic (hereinafter referred to as ‘SR’) was carried out by the Finance and Tax Office of the SAO of the Slovak Republic in cooperation with the expositories of the SAO of Banská Bystrica and Košice at 5 customs offices out of a total of 9 between 13 February and 2 June 2006.</seg>
<seg id="23">Eight inspectors were involved in the inspection.</seg>
