<doc docid="testsuite-segment_65-KA_09_11_OCR" genre="news" origlang="en" sysid="CUNI-Transformer2018">
<p>
<seg id="1">Value Added Tax Administration in the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany</seg>
<seg id="2">Report on follow-up results</seg>
<seg id="3">Introduction Word</seg>
<seg id="4">Taxes in general are a key source of public revenue.</seg>
<seg id="5">It goes without saying that Supreme Audit Institutions (SAIs) should focus their attention on this area.</seg>
<seg id="6">Value added tax (VAT) fraud is an example.</seg>
<seg id="7">In their case, a loss of EUR 100 billion is estimated each year in the European Union (EU).</seg>
<seg id="8">As early as 2005, attendees of the VIth EUROSAI Congress in Bonn agreed on the need for very close cooperation.</seg>
<seg id="9">As part of this cooperation, SAIs can exchange control procedures, find the best solutions, etc.</seg>
<seg id="10">VAT is a very suitable area for control cooperation as it is the only tax harmonised within the EU.</seg>
<seg id="11">The Supreme Audit Office of the Czech Republic (hereinafter also referred to as the SAO) and the Federal Court of Auditors (Bundesrechnungshof, hereinafter also referred to as BRH) carried out the first parallel VAT control action in 2006.</seg>
<seg id="12">The report was published in 2008.</seg>
<seg id="13">As VAT fraud is not limited to a single country, but is widespread across the EU, close cooperation between the SAIs is needed to ensure a comprehensive assessment of the steps being taken to address the problem.</seg>
<seg id="14">The two SAIs therefore decided to further develop cooperation in this area and carried out a follow-up parallel check.</seg>
<seg id="15">1. Introduction</seg>
<seg id="16">Control number: (CZ) 09/11 (D) VIII 2 - 2009 - 0892</seg>
<seg id="17">Subject of the audit: (CZ) Value Added Tax Administration (D) Bilateral audit with the SAO (follow-up)</seg>
<seg id="18">Target of control:</seg>
<seg id="19">(CZ) The objective of the audit operation was to examine the VAT administration procedure of the tax authorities, in particular to verify the procedure for dealing with selected cases of commercial transactions between the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany (hereinafter referred to as "Germany"), and to examine the procedures of the tax administrations of the two countries in the framework of international cooperation.</seg>
<seg id="20">(D) The audit action was designed to evaluate the measures taken by the tax administration to implement the recommendations issued by the SAO and BRH.</seg>
<seg id="21">It was also intended to cover other areas related to VAT.</seg>
<seg id="22">The resulting control findings were intended to compare with established good practice (if any).</seg>
<seg id="23">The audited period was the years 2006 to 2008 and, where relevant, the period before and after, until the end of the auditing period.</seg>
<seg id="24">2. Summary of results and evaluation of parallel control actions</seg>
<seg id="25">A follow-up inspection of the VAT administration in the Czech Republic and Germany was carried out on the basis of an agreement between the two SAIs.</seg>
<seg id="26">Suspicious cases of intra-Community transactions have been identified during previous parallel checks.</seg>
<seg id="27">Some of them required further screening.</seg>
<seg id="28">Based on the audit findings, both SAIs formulated recommendations on VAT administration.</seg>
<seg id="29">The follow-up was carried out to evaluate the actions taken in response to these recommendations and to examine selected suspected cases.</seg>
<seg id="30">The audit further focused on e.g. selected cases of high-risk intra-Community transactions, mutual assistance in the recovery of claims and the carrying out of VAT checks on large tax entities.</seg>
<seg id="31">When reviewing the VAT administration in selected areas in both countries, the auditors made the following control findings:</seg>
<seg id="32">1. Recommendations from previous check</seg>
<seg id="33">• Recommendation 1: Payer registration conditions should be harmonised across the EU</seg>
<seg id="34">In previous parallel controls, a comparison of VAT registration systems in the two countries identified differences.</seg>
<seg id="35">As different ways of registering cause problems, both SAIs recommended harmonising the conditions for registering payers within the EU.</seg>
<seg id="36">This recommendation has been made at EU level.</seg>
<seg id="37">The proposal to amend Council Regulation (EC) No 1798/2003 on administrative cooperation in the field of value added tax and repealing Regulation (EEC) No 218/92 (hereinafter referred to as "Council Regulation (EC) No 1798/2003") called for the extension of existing databases within the EU, including the database of VAT payers' tax identification numbers.</seg>
<seg id="38">He also amended the common standards for the registration and deregistration of taxpayers.</seg>
<seg id="39">The SAIs expected EU Member States to agree on adequate standards to support their decision to exclude unreliable traders from the VAT system as quickly as possible.</seg>
<seg id="40">However, the latest version of that document, agreed by the EU Member States under ECOFIN, no longer contains the issue.</seg>
<seg id="41">Both SAIs regret that the idea of common minimum standards has been abandoned.</seg>
<seg id="42">However, they continue to regard this intention as a relevant prevention tool in the fight against VAT fraud.</seg>
<seg id="43">• Recommendation 2: Monthly reporting of recapitulative statements</seg>
<seg id="44">In the context of international cooperation, a previous control action recommended that all EU states introduce a monthly reporting period to allow for more timely examination of intra-Community transaction values.</seg>
<seg id="45">Council Directive 2008/117/EC amending Directive 2006/112/EC on the common system of value added tax to combat tax evasion connected with intra-Community transactions reduces the reporting period for recapitulative statements on intra-EU transactions to one month.</seg>
<seg id="46">In the Czech Republic this measure was implemented through the Value Added Tax Act with effect from 1 January 2010, in Germany it was implemented from 1 July 2010.</seg>
<seg id="47">In Germany, the obligation to file recapitulative statements on a monthly basis was not introduced by the deadline in accordance with the applicable EU rules, while in the Czech Republic it was.</seg>
<seg id="48">• Recommendation 3: Comparison of data in VAT returns and recapitulative statements in Germany with a view to making VIES data more reliable and considering linking the two systems for VAT returns and recapitulative statements</seg>
<seg id="49">The German tax administration accepted the BRH's recommendations and set up a working group to explore possible solutions.</seg>
<seg id="50">Work is still ongoing and BRH will closely monitor further developments.</seg>
<seg id="51">• Recommendation 4: Sharing successful criteria, components and approaches of a risk management system at EU level Based on the results of the previous control action, both SAIs agreed that an effective risk management system cannot be developed by just one Member State.</seg>
<seg id="52">Successful risk management system criteria, components and approaches need to be exchanged and implemented in individual EU Member States.</seg>
<seg id="53">If this is not the case, the perpetrators of the fraudulent activity will choose the Member State with the weakest risk management system.</seg>
<seg id="54">The audit found that our two Member States use different risk management systems, which have their strengths and weaknesses.</seg>
<seg id="55">In this area, the SAO audited EUROCANET, which allows information exchange within the EU, while BRH concentrated on German participation in the so-called risk management platform.</seg>
<seg id="56">2. Follow-up of selected intra-Community transaction cases</seg>
<seg id="57">During the previous audit operation, business transactions were jointly examined where there were doubts about their execution or irregularities in the reporting of business transactions on tax returns or recapitulative statements by tax payers from both countries.</seg>
<seg id="58">The two SAIs selected for follow-up nine cases involving intra-Community movement of goods between the Czech Republic and Germany.</seg>
<seg id="59">The checks carried out by the tax authorities of the respective countries have not been completed by the date of completion of our previous joint control action.</seg>
<seg id="60">A follow-up action verified that most of the tax proceedings in relation to the specified selected cases of commercial transactions between payers from the Czech Republic and Germany had been concluded and that adequate measures had been taken by the tax administration of the Czech Republic or Germany (e.g. additional VAT assessments or avoidance of input tax refunds).</seg>
<seg id="61">3. Control of selected cases of risky intra-community transactions</seg>
<seg id="62">High-risk cases of intra-Community transactions by EU payers enrolled in EUROCANET were selected for the check.</seg>
<seg id="63">EUROCANET is a tool for detecting risky taxpayers within the EU.</seg>
<seg id="64">The participation of Member States in this scheme is voluntary.</seg>
<seg id="65">The Czech Republic is an active participant in EUROCANET, while Germany has a passive status.</seg>
<seg id="66">It is unsatisfactory for an active participant in the scheme if some Member States refuse active participation.</seg>
<seg id="67">Due to the fact that the German tax administration was not involved in the exchange of data in EUROCANET, no information could be obtained on which suppliers with German VAT IDs were assessed as being at risk.</seg>
<seg id="68">In the framework of the audit operation, the SAO found both cases of normal commercial transactions and cases of suspected involvement in carousel transactions or fraudulent VAT activities.</seg>
<seg id="69">Tax authorities have limited means of controlling risky transactions, particularly when it comes to missing traders, and mere physical examination of documents can make it difficult to prove any fraudulent behaviour to the taxpayer.</seg>
<seg id="70">A similar situation for tax administrations arises when imports and exports to third countries are linked to intra-Community carousel shops.</seg>
<seg id="71">In such cases, it would be appropriate to ensure greater co-operation between customs and financial authorities to identify goods and irregularities in transport documentation, as well as to monitor their physical movement within the EU towards the final consumer.</seg>
<seg id="72">Germany, like some other countries, is hesitant to actively participate in EUROCANET due to the lack of a sufficient legal basis.</seg>
<seg id="73">In Germany, other instruments are being used to detect at-risk taxpayers, which have so far proved successful for the German tax administration.</seg>
<seg id="74">In this area, there is a need to communicate and exchange experiences between EU Member States.</seg>
<seg id="75">The EU Council has reached a political consensus on the proposal for a Regulation amending Council Regulation (EC) No 1798/2003.</seg>
<seg id="76">Its main innovation is the creation of the EUROFISC network.</seg>
<seg id="77">The experience gained so far in using EUROCANET should underpin the creation of this new network to fight VAT fraud.</seg>
<seg id="78">4. Mutual assistance for recovery of claims</seg>
<seg id="79">In the area of international recovery assistance, all EU Member States follow the same European legislation.</seg>
<seg id="80">Therefore, the way in which applications for international recovery assistance are handled is identical in the Czech Republic and Germany.</seg>
<seg id="81">The SAO and BRH compared the statistics submitted by the two Member States to the European Commission for the years 2006-2008.</seg>
<seg id="82">The data contained in these statistics did not match.</seg>
<seg id="83">Both SAIs find it useful to renegotiate the statistics at EU level in order to find a way to avoid persistent mismatches.</seg>
<seg id="84">Without this, the statistics will not be reliable and comparable.</seg>
<seg id="85">In addition, SAIs agree that reliable statistics should include more information on VAT.</seg>
<seg id="86">It would probably be useful for the Commission to produce an analysis, based on more detailed statistics, to help Member States strengthen the effectiveness of the fight against VAT fraud.</seg>
<seg id="87">In both SAIs' view, this means helping Member States with low recovery rates to be able to raise recovery rates to at least the EU average.</seg>
<seg id="88">If a Member State so wishes, the Commission should actively participate in the process.</seg>
<seg id="89">5. Control of large tax entities</seg>
<seg id="90">The SAIs analysed the legal situation regarding VAT control of large tax entities (VDS) in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="91">In addition, they gathered information from tax administrations in the form of a questionnaire on areas that SAIs consider essential for the management of this issue.</seg>
<seg id="92">The responses received clearly show that the situation in the two countries is developing differently.</seg>
<seg id="93">The Czech Republic has a system in place to guide the selection of risk-prone cases, relying on a large volume of relevant data (e.g. information from tax checks carried out, balance sheet data and profit and loss accounts, etc.).</seg>
<seg id="94">This ensures the effective management and analysis of VAT control in general.</seg>
<seg id="95">The establishment of a dedicated financial office for the management of VDS is planned in 2012.</seg>
<seg id="96">In Germany, a similar system does not yet exist, making it difficult to manage and analyse VAT controls in general.</seg>
<seg id="97">Germany has so far concentrated more on selecting the individual cases in question, mainly on the basis of data from the VAT return and recapitulative statement.</seg>
<seg id="98">The analysis of this data relies on various risk management components which will be strengthened.</seg>
<seg id="99">3. Control Action Progress</seg>
<seg id="100">3.1 Czech Republic Follow-up</seg>
<seg id="101">The audit was carried out between May 2009 and February 2010 by Division II - the revenue department of the state budget and territorial departments IX. Plzeň, X. České Budějovice, XIII. Brno and XV. Ostrava.</seg>
<seg id="102">The audited persons were: the Ministry of Finance of the Czech Republic (hereinafter also referred to as the Czech Ministry of Finance) and 25 financial offices (hereinafter also referred to as the ‘FIU’): FÚ Brno II, FÚ Brno III, FÚ Brno IV, FÚ Brno in Břeclav, FÚ BrÚ Vary, FÚ VÚ in Domestic, FÚ BrÚFÚ FÚFÚFÚ in PraÚFÚFÚ KrÚFÚFÚ, FÚ ÚFÚFÚFÚ I and FÚFÚFÚFÚFÚ FÚ I8, FÚ</seg>
<seg id="103">The audit conclusion from this audit action was approved by the College of the Supreme Audit Office on 27 April 2010.</seg>
<seg id="104">3.2 Conduct of the inspection operation in Germany</seg>
<seg id="105">The audit was carried out between February 2009 and February 2010 by the Indirect Taxation Control Unit and the personnel of the designated regional audit offices in Berlin, Frankfurt am Main and Munich.</seg>
<seg id="106">Following the selection of a sample of cases, a number of Länder were notified of the mission of the inspection operation.</seg>
<seg id="107">In addition to the interviews at the Federal Ministry of Finance, a control event took place in the following Länder: • Bavaria, • Hamburg, • Hessen, • North Rhine-Westphalia, • Saxony.</seg>
<seg id="108">The tax files of the following tax authorities were included: • Erlangen, Zentralfinanzamt München (Central Tax Office in Munich), Hof, Schwandorf, Regensburg, Weiden in der Oberpfalz, Grafenau; • Hamburg-Nord (Hamburg-sever), Hamburg-Hansa, Hamburg für Großunternehmen (Hamburg-VDS);</seg>
<seg id="109">In addition, discussions took place with the fiscal authorities of Mühlacker, Reutlingen, Starnberg, Verden, Erfurt, Leipzig, Halle-Süd (Halle-jih) and the finance directorates in Frankfurt am Main, Chemnitz and Münster.</seg>
<seg id="110">A report on the inspection findings was submitted to the Federal Ministry of Finance in April 2010.</seg>
<seg id="111">3.3 Cooperation between the two audit institutions</seg>
<seg id="112">In preparation for the parallel audit events, a meeting of representatives of the two audit institutions was held in September 2008 to discuss and identify topics of control.</seg>
<seg id="113">Subsequently, in December 2008, the leaders of the two SAIs signed an agreement to cooperate in carrying out parallel controls.</seg>
<seg id="114">At a meeting in Bonn in June 2009, the control teams informed each other of the initial results achieved in the course of preparing the inspection, discussed possible audit approaches and agreed on a course of action.</seg>
<seg id="115">The second meeting took place in Prague on 2-4 December 2009.</seg>
<seg id="116">The review teams exchanged the findings collected so far and agreed on a timetable for compiling a joint report.</seg>
<seg id="117">The two SAIs, in carrying out parallel control actions, decided to focus on: • a follow-up of the implementation of the recommendations made in the previous report; • an examination of selected cases of intra-Community transactions between tax payers from the Czech Republic and Germany that were not resolved during the previous parallel check; • an examination of selected cases of intra-Community transactions between tax payers from the Czech Republic and Germany that were classified as high risk; • a review of the tax administration's procedure in the area of international assistance for the recovery of VAT receivables; • tax controls of large companies.</seg>
<seg id="118">A report on the results of the parallel control actions was prepared during a workshop in June 2010.</seg>
<seg id="119">4. Control of VAT administration in selected areas</seg>
<seg id="120">4.1 Evaluation of previous review recommendations</seg>
<seg id="121">4.1.1 Evaluation of recommendations in the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="122">Recommendation 1</seg>
<seg id="123">Payer registration conditions should be harmonised across the EU</seg>
<seg id="124">Based on the results of the previous audit action, the SAO recommended the modification of the conditions of VAT registration and the introduction of a new rule for the cancellation of registration in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="125">The modified conditions should make it possible to reduce more effectively the risk of possible tax evasion in the collection of VAT.</seg>
<seg id="126">In this context, it was found that in some cases the tax authorities did not use the power to cancel VAT registration to taxpayers who did not comply with the obligations under Act No 235/2004 Coll. on Value Added Tax (‘the VAT Act’).</seg>
<seg id="127">The amendment of the provision to introduce the obligation for tax administrations to cancel the VAT registration of payers upon repeated non-submission of a VAT return has not yet been proposed by the Czech Ministry of Finance.</seg>
<seg id="128">Under the VAT Act, the tax authority may revoke the registration of the taxpayer ‘ex officio’ in cases where: (a) the taxpayer has not, without giving notice of the reason to the tax authority, carried out a transaction for 12 consecutive months; (b) the taxpayer has failed to fulfil his obligations under this Act; (c) the taxpayer ceases to be a taxable person.</seg>
<seg id="129">In a previous audit action, it was found that the legislation in force allowed the Tax Office for Threshold 1 to cancel VAT registration on 31 January of the following calendar year to so-called non-established payers who had not incurred any obligation to declare and pay tax during the current calendar year.</seg>
<seg id="130">Often, the FVO for Threshold 1 did not revoke these taxpayers' VAT registration, as the relevant provision provided an insufficient deadline for deregistration.</seg>
<seg id="131">This problem was eliminated by amending the VAT Act with effect from 1 January 2009.</seg>
<seg id="132">The tax authorities shall be entitled to cancel the registration of the non-established taxpayer where the taxpayer has not supplied any goods or services subject to tax or exempt goods or services with a right to deduct VAT in the preceding calendar year.</seg>
<seg id="133">Recommendation 2</seg>
<seg id="134">Monthly reporting of recapitulative statements</seg>
<seg id="135">In the context of international cooperation, a previous control action recommended that all EU states introduce a one-month deadline for the submission of recapitulative statements.</seg>
<seg id="136">The Council Directive reduces the reporting period for recapitulative statements on intra-EU transactions to one month. This measure was implemented in the Czech Republic through the VAT Act with effect from 1 January 2010.</seg>
<seg id="137">There is also a new obligation to file recapitulative statements in electronic form.</seg>
<seg id="138">A summary report must also be made by the payer if the services for which the place of supply is determined in accordance with Paragraph 9(1) of the VAT Code are supplied to a person registered for tax in another Member State and the recipient is obliged to declare and pay the tax on those services.</seg>
<seg id="139">This obligation is based on Council Directive 2008/8/EC amending Directive 2006/112/EC as regards the place of supply of the service.</seg>
<seg id="140">Recommendation 3</seg>
<seg id="141">Comparison of data in VAT returns and recapitulative reports to achieve higher data reliability in VIES This recommendation concerned the German tax administration.</seg>
<seg id="142">The Czech administration conducts comparisons of intra-Community transaction data reported in VAT returns and summary reports of Czech payers automated in the ADIS system.</seg>
<seg id="143">Recommendation 4</seg>
<seg id="144">Sharing successful criteria, components and approaches of a risk management system at EU level</seg>
<seg id="145">Proper collection of VAT is one of the prerequisites for the proper functioning of the EU internal market.</seg>
<seg id="146">Combating VAT fraud is therefore an area of priority concern and has received considerable attention in recent years.</seg>
<seg id="147">The importance of this fight is evidenced, inter alia, by the conclusions of a study published by the European Commission in October 2009, in which an external evaluator attempted to establish the difference between the eligible and the actual VAT collected in the 25 EU Member States (hereinafter referred to as the EU-25) during the period 2000-2006.</seg>
<seg id="148">Based on an analysis of the available data, the author of the analysis concludes that the estimated amount of loss of uncollected VAT for this period is between €90 and €113 billion, with an average of 12% of eligible VAT not collected annually in the EU-25.</seg>
<seg id="149">For the Czech Republic, the VAT loss for 2006 was even estimated at 18%.</seg>
<seg id="150">In the context of international cooperation, a previous control action found that an effective risk management system could not be developed by just one Member State.</seg>
<seg id="151">The successful criteria, components and approaches of this system must be shared and implemented in every EU Member State.</seg>
<seg id="152">Regarding the risk management system, the SAO carried out a check of EUROCANET, a system used to exchange information in the EU.</seg>
<seg id="153">Cases of risky intra-Community transactions by EU tax payers included in EUROCANET were selected for the check (see Chapter 4.3).</seg>
<seg id="154">The objectives of improving administrative cooperation and increasing the effectiveness of the fight against VAT fraud should also be achieved through the establishment of the EUROFISC network, which should help to improve the cooperation of the responsible authorities into a form that allows fraud to be detected in its infancy.</seg>
<seg id="155">This network should later also become an important source of information in risk assessment for intra-Community transactions.</seg>
<seg id="156">The ECOFIN Council approved the creation of the EUROFISC network on 7 October 200812, while setting out the basic principles that will guide the network.</seg>
<seg id="157">The EUROFISC picture is the already functioning EUROCANET fast and selective information exchange system, developed by the Belgian tax administration in cooperation with other Member States and with the support of the European Commission and OLAF.</seg>
<seg id="158">The aim of this system is to detect risky business transactions and entities involved in organised VAT fraud.</seg>
<seg id="159">4.1.2 Evaluation of recommendations in Germany</seg>
<seg id="160">The evaluation of the recommendations of the first report produced the following findings:</seg>
<seg id="161">Recommendation 1</seg>
<seg id="162">Payer registration conditions should be harmonised across the EU</seg>
<seg id="163">The German tax administration has set up a well-functioning system for registering taxpayers, based on a detailed questionnaire.</seg>
<seg id="164">The Federal Ministry of Finance brought the scheme to the attention of the Commission in October 2007.</seg>
<seg id="165">Improvements to the system are made on an ongoing basis.</seg>
<seg id="166">Currently, the questionnaire data is electronically processed and will subsequently be used for the survey as part of risk management already during registration.</seg>
<seg id="167">The Commission presented a proposal to amend Council Regulation (EC) No 1798/2003 which included common standards for the registration and deregistration of taxpayers.</seg>
<seg id="168">Member States have requested further clarification and detailed elaboration of this issue.</seg>
<seg id="169">BRH has asked the Federal Ministry of Finance to safeguard the level of standards already achieved in this area in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="170">Recommendation 2</seg>
<seg id="171">Monthly reporting of recapitulative statements</seg>
<seg id="172">A law on the transposition of EU directives into national law was adopted on 8 April 2010.</seg>
<seg id="173">That law includes provisions for the monthly submission of recapitulative statements on intra-Community deliveries.</seg>
<seg id="174">Those provisions took effect on 1 July 2010.</seg>
<seg id="175">Recommendation 3</seg>
<seg id="176">Comparison of data in VAT returns and recapitulative statements in order to achieve greater data reliability in VIES and consider linking the two VAT return and recapitulative reporting systems</seg>
<seg id="177">A joint working group was set up, made up of staff from the Länder and the Federal Ministry of Finance.</seg>
<seg id="178">The group has developed a strategy for automatically comparing data from VAT returns and recapitulative statements.</seg>
<seg id="179">This strategy is still being discussed in the Länder.</seg>
<seg id="180">Furthermore, the working group looked at a tool designed to optimise the control process for transactions in the internal market.</seg>
<seg id="181">Recommendation 4</seg>
<seg id="182">Sharing successful criteria, components and approaches of a risk management system at EU level The exchange of relevant information takes place at EU level.</seg>
<seg id="183">Germany is a participant in this exchange under the so-called Risk Management Platform.</seg>
<seg id="184">The European Commission supported the idea of the platform and, following a written consultation on 18 October 2006, the establishment of the Risk Management Platform was added to the Fiscalis Action Plan 2006-2007.</seg>
<seg id="185">The members of the platform are further divided into sub-groups that address individual topics such as: • risk management tools; • influencing behaviour; • evaluation; • updating the risk management guide.</seg>
